# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: honshu
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The **Great Kantō Earthquake** (Japanese: 関東大地震, *Kantō daijishin*, or 関東大震災, *Kantō daishinsai*) was a megathrust earthquake that struck the Kantō Plain on the main Japanese island of Honshu at 11:58:32 JST (02:58:32 UTC) on Saturday, 1 September 1923.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] It had an approximate magnitude of 8.0 on the moment magnitude scale (Mw), with its epicenter located some 100 km (62 mi) southwest of the capital Tokyo.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake devastated Tokyo, the port city of Yokohama, and the surrounding prefectures of Kanagawa, Chiba, and Shizuoka, causing widespread damage throughout the Kantō region.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The event was a complex disaster, with modern research indicating it consisted of three consecutive shocks in the span of several minutes.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The initial megathrust event in Kanagawa Prefecture was followed three minutes later by a magnitude 7.2 earthquake centered beneath Tokyo Bay, and two minutes after that by a magnitude 7.3 shock in Yamanashi Prefecture.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Fires, exacerbated by strong winds from a nearby typhoon, spread rapidly through the densely populated urban areas, accounting for the majority of the devastation and casualties.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The death toll is estimated to have been between 105,000 and 140,000 people, including tens of thousands who went missing and were presumed dead.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Over half of Tokyo and nearly all of Yokohama were destroyed, leaving approximately 2.5 million people homeless.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster triggered widespread social unrest, including the Kantō Massacre, in which ethnic Koreans and others mistaken for them were murdered by vigilante groups based on false rumors.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] In the aftermath, the Japanese government declared martial law and undertook extensive relief and restoration efforts.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake prompted ambitious plans for the reconstruction of Tokyo, aiming to create a modern, resilient imperial capital under the leadership of Home Minister Gotō Shinpei.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] However, these plans were often met with political contestation, financial constraints, and local resistance, leading to a reconstruction that, while significantly improving infrastructure, fell short of the grandest visions.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster also fueled debates about national identity, modernity, and societal values, with many commentators interpreting the event as a divine punishment for perceived moral decline and advocating for spiritual and social regeneration.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Great Kantō Earthquake remains a pivotal event in modern Japanese history, profoundly impacting urban planning, disaster preparedness, and social consciousness.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] 1 September is commemorated annually in Japan as Disaster Prevention Day.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Kantō region of eastern Japan is prone to major earthquakes due to its location near complex tectonic plate boundaries.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The 1923 earthquake occurred when the Philippine Sea Plate subducted beneath the Okhotsk Plate (sometimes considered part of the North American Plate) along the Sagami Trough.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The initial shock, occurring at 11:58:32 JST on 1 September 1923, was a complex event.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Modern analysis indicates a dual rupture on a broad trench-type fault: the first rupture occurred near Odawara in Kanagawa Prefecture, some 100 km (62 mi) southwest of Tokyo, followed about ten seconds later by a second shock on the other side of Sagami Bay near the Miura Peninsula.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] This was followed minutes later by two major aftershocks: a magnitude 7.2 earthquake beneath northern Tokyo Bay at 12:01, and a magnitude 7.3 earthquake in Yamanashi Prefecture at 12:03.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Survivor accounts consistently describe these three distinct seismic events.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake immediately toppled structures, crushed people, and caused widespread panic.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Survivor accounts describe an initial period of stunned silence followed by a frantic rush as people tried to reunite with family and salvage belongings.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Engineer Mononobe Nagao recalled the earth shaking "back and forth for what seemed like 15 seconds", followed by violent vertical convulsions that knocked people to the ground.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Writer Tanaka Kōtarō described the sound as akin to a giant "blackening whirlwind" churning up the earth from "deep underground".
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Within thirty minutes of the first tremor, more than 130 major fires broke out across Tokyo, particularly in the densely populated eastern and northeastern sections.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] These fires were fueled by overturned charcoal braziers used for midday meals, leaking gas from ruptured lines, and flammable debris from collapsed wooden buildings.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Strong winds, associated with a typhoon passing off the coast, fanned the flames, creating massive firestorms that swept through the city.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The air temperature in some areas reached 46 °C (115 °F).
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The combination of ongoing aftershocks and rapidly spreading fires led to pandemonium.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Millions of residents attempted to flee, often carrying their possessions, which clogged the already damaged streets and bridges.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Kawatake Shigetoshi described being trapped in a "wave of people" in eastern Tokyo, unable to move as fires approached from multiple directions.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Many sought refuge in open spaces, such as parks and the grounds surrounding the Imperial Palace, but these areas quickly became overcrowded.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Waterways like the Sumida River also became congested with boats as people tried to escape by water, only to face sparks and burning debris falling from the sky.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster quickly overwhelmed Tokyo's infrastructure and its capacity for an orderly evacuation.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Great Kantō Earthquake was one of the most destructive natural disasters of the 20th century.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Roughly half of Tokyo and virtually all of Yokohama were transformed into "blackened, corpse-strewn wastelands".
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake and subsequent fires destroyed an estimated 397,119 homes in Tokyo Prefecture alone, leaving about 1.38 million people homeless in Tokyo City.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Across the seven affected prefectures (Tokyo, Kanagawa, Chiba, Saitama, Shizuoka, Yamanashi, and Ibaraki), a total of 2.5 million people were displaced.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] In addition to buildings, the earthquake buckled roads, collapsed bridges (362 destroyed and 70 heavily damaged in Tokyo), twisted train tracks, snapped water and sewer pipes, and severed telegraph lines.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Tokyo's main aqueduct from Wadabori collapsed in two places and required extensive repairs.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The sea floor in Sagami Bay dropped by over 400 meters (1,300 ft) at the epicenter, triggering tsunamis that inundated low-lying coastal communities.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Fires were the primary cause of destruction, accounting for 90 percent of the fatalities.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] In Tokyo, districts like Asakusa, Kanda, Nihonbashi, Kyōbashi, Honjo, and Fukagawa were largely incinerated.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Honjo Clothing Depot, a large open area where tens of thousands sought refuge, became a death trap when a massive firestorm (a *tatsumaki* or whirlwind of fire) engulfed it, killing an estimated 40,000 people in minutes.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Survivor Koizumi Tomi described the site as "hell on earth", surrounded by "endless rows of bodies: red, inflamed bodies; black, swollen bodies; bodies partially buried under ash and smoldering remains".
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The government administration was crippled.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] In Tokyo, 44 percent of the main buildings burned to the ground, including the police headquarters and the ministries of Home Affairs, Finance, Education, Communications, and Railways.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The vast majority of police stations and municipal and ward offices crumbled or burned.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Out of Tokyo's 196 primary schools, 117 were destroyed, along with numerous higher girls' schools, trade schools, colleges, and universities.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Social welfare facilities, including public dining halls, cheap lodging homes, and crèches, were annihilated.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Over 160 public and private hospitals in Tokyo were destroyed.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster exacerbated the economic downturn of the early 1920s and contributed to a genuine banking crisis in 1927.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Roughly 7,000 factories were destroyed, including major spinning, dyeing, and tool manufacturing plants.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Financial institutions suffered heavily, with 121 of 138 bank head offices and 222 of 310 branch offices in Tokyo City consumed by fire or reduced to rubble.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Insurance policies offered little relief, as most contained clauses exempting companies from earthquake-related damage; eventually, the government intervened to facilitate partial payouts.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Reconstruction brought a new surge of imports and, under these combined pressures, an early return to the gold standard was impossible.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster also led to significant unemployment.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] In September 1923, the unemployment rate in the wards of Tokyo reached 45% (59% for men, 28% for women).
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] By 15 November, across Tokyo Prefecture, 178,887 people were registered as unemployed, with the commerce and industry sectors most affected.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The human toll of the Great Kantō Earthquake was catastrophic.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Early estimates put the death toll as high as 140,000, but modern research based on the *1923 Great Kantō Earthquake Disaster Report* puts the total number of fatalities at 105,385.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Of these, 91,781 deaths (87%) were attributed to fires, while 11,086 (10.5%) were due to being crushed by collapsing buildings.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Other causes included drowning and landslides.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Kanagawa Prefecture suffered 32,838 deaths, while Tokyo Prefecture had 70,387.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] An additional 13,275 people remained classified as missing twelve months after the earthquake.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] People died in numerous ways: crushed by collapsing buildings, trampled in panicked crowds, burned alive in the fires, or drowned in rivers and canals while attempting to escape the flames.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Some victims suffocated as fires consumed oxygen, while others were boiled alive in ponds offering no protection from the intense heat.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The smell of burning human flesh and decaying bodies permeated the air for weeks.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Disposing of the dead became a major public health concern, leading to mass cremations, particularly at the Honjo Clothing Depot.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] In the immediate aftermath of the earthquake, law and order broke down in many parts of the affected region.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] This period was characterized by the spread of rumors, the formation of vigilante groups (*jikeidan*), and the massacre of ethnic Koreans and others mistaken for them, as well as the murder of political activists by the authorities.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Widespread destruction of communication infrastructure contributed to an atmosphere of uncertainty and fear.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Rumors spread rapidly, often relayed by refugees fleeing the disaster zone.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Some stories suggested that Mount Fuji had erupted or that a large tsunami had washed away Yokohama.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The most damaging rumors, however, concerned alleged activities by Koreans.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Originating from looting by Japanese in Yokohama that was misattributed to Koreans, false reports circulated that Koreans were poisoning wells, committing arson, looting, and organizing attacks on Japanese.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] These rumors were given a degree of legitimacy when some government officials, including Gotō Fumio of the Home Ministry, broadcast messages warning of "organized groups of Korean extremists" attempting to "commit acts of sedition".
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] On 2 September, the police headquarters, lacking manpower to confirm eyewitness reports, passed them on as factual and issued a statement that "unscrupulous Koreans are committing acts of arson and other forms of violence".
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Fueled by these rumors and a climate of fear and xenophobia, Japanese vigilante groups, known as *jikeidan*, formed across the Kantō region.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] By mid-September, an estimated 3,689 such groups were operating, ostensibly to prevent fires, stop looting, and maintain order.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] However, many of these groups, often armed with makeshift weapons like clubs, swords, and bamboo spears, targeted Koreans and, in some cases, Chinese, Okinawans, and Japanese from certain regions who were mistaken for Koreans due to their accents.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Estimates of the death toll in what became known as the Kantō Massacre vary significantly.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Police confirmed the deaths of 248 Koreans, while an investigation by the Governor-General of Korea determined 832 had been killed or were missing.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] A separate investigation by Korean students concluded that 2,613 Koreans had been killed; some modern estimates reach as high as 6,000.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Victims were often subjected to brutal violence, including beatings, stabbings, and lynchings, sometimes after being "tested" for their Korean identity (e.g., by being asked to pronounce Japanese words that were difficult for Koreans).
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] While some police and military personnel attempted to protect Koreans, others were complicit in the violence or turned a blind eye.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Although police made belated corrections to the rumors on 3 and 4 September, few perpetrators were prosecuted; of 125 vigilante group members tried, only 32 received formal sentences, and 91 received suspended sentences.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Contemporary commentators like Hoashi Ri'ichirō and Oku Hidesaburō condemned the massacres as "extremely disgusting and internationally shameful" and a "disgraceful act that exposed a moral flaw".
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The chaos also provided a cover for the murder of political dissidents.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The most prominent case was the Amakasu Incident, in which the anarchist Sakae Ōsugi, his partner Noe Itō, and his six-year-old nephew were arrested and then brutally killed by a squad of military police led by Lieutenant Masahiko Amakasu.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake struck at a time of political uncertainty in Japan.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Prime Minister Katō Tomosaburō had died on 24 August, and Admiral Yamamoto Gonnohyōe, selected to form a new cabinet, had not yet succeeded when the disaster occurred.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster also forced the postponement of Crown Prince Hirohito's marriage and accession ceremonies.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] This elite-level political vacuum contributed to confusion over who had the authority to deploy police and military personnel.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] General Ishimitsu Maomi, deputy commander of the Imperial Guard Forces, acted first, deploying troops to protect imperial locations.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Akaike Atsushi, inspector general of the Tokyo Metropolitan Police, faced an overwhelming task with outnumbered and unprepared forces.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The new cabinet was formally appointed on the afternoon of 2 September, sworn in on the lawn of the Akasaka Detached Palace amid falling ash, as other ministerial buildings were deemed unsafe.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] One of the first decisions of the new cabinet was to declare martial law over what remained of the capital on 2 September.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] This ushered in the largest peacetime domestic mobilization and deployment of the army in Japan's pre–World War II history, with eventually over 52,000 troops deployed to Tokyo and Yokohama.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The martial law headquarters was granted extensive powers, including administering relief and public safety, prosecuting lawbreakers, prohibiting public gatherings, censoring information, stopping and searching individuals, and entering private homes.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Martial law remained in effect until 15 November.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Initial military deployment was fraught with difficulties.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Commanders arriving in Tokyo found a near total absence of reliable information and lines of communication were non-existent.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The military had to rely on aerial reconnaissance and around 2,000 army-trained carrier pigeons for communication.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The zone of martial law was progressively expanded to cover all of Tokyo and Kanagawa Prefectures by 3 September, and Chiba and Saitama Prefectures by 4 September.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] To counter rumors and vigilante violence, particularly against Koreans, military authorities were empowered to arrest individuals, disband suspicious groups, and confiscate weapons.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] From 4 September, military and police began to collect and transport Koreans to government-run detention centers for "protective custody"; by the end of September, 23,715 Koreans had been taken into these centers.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Yamamoto cabinet created the Emergency Earthquake Relief Bureau (*Rinji shinsai kyūgo jimukyoku*) to oversee all relief and recovery efforts.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Providing emergency medical assistance was an immediate priority, but initial efforts were largely unsuccessful.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Many organized rescue and first aid squads were unable to reach the worst-hit areas like Honjo, Asakusa, and Kanda until 4 or 5 September due to destroyed infrastructure and unofficial checkpoints by vigilante groups.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] A dearth of medical supplies, due to the destruction of numerous hospitals and dispensaries, further hampered efforts.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Relief Bureau concentrated its limited medical resources at large open areas like Hibiya Park and Ueno Park, where tens of thousands of refugees had congregated.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Over the longer term, mobile clinics and dispensaries proved most effective.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Relief Bureau created 41 units, and other organizations like Tokyo Prefecture, the Japan Red Cross Society, and the Mitsubishi Corporation also operated mobile clinics.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] By 30 November, these public and private clinics had provided care to 447,111 sufferers.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Temporary hospitals, some in tents donated by American and French governments, accommodated over 6,000 seriously wounded people.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Securing food and water was a critical challenge.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Mayor Hidejirō Nagata learned on 2 September that the army's main supply depot in Fukagawa, holding 8,000 *koku* of rice (enough to feed over 500,000 people for six days), had been completely destroyed by fire.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The military managed to amass over 120,000 combat rations and 60,000 rations of rice from other stores.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] By 4 September, military units were distributing dried noodles.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Eventually, 74,048 *koku* of rice were transported from military installations across Japan to distribution centers in Tokyo and Yokohama.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The government also appealed to prefectural governors for rice donations, receiving pledges of 61,490 *koku* in the first week.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] An "Emergency Requisition Ordinance" allowed the government to requisition foodstuffs and other materials.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Transporting these supplies was a major logistical challenge due to damaged rail lines and docks.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Navy personnel spent a week repairing 86 piers at Shibaura and Ryōgoku, while army forces cleared railway lines and rebuilt track.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Conservative estimates suggest that 1.25 million people received rice distributions between 6 and 10 September.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Water supply was an even more significant problem.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Tokyo's main water plant was not heavily damaged, but pipes and aquifers were severed in over two hundred locations.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Warships tanked water from Yokosuka, Osaka, and Nagoya, and the army requisitioned water barrels to transport clean water.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] By the end of December, nearly 40 million gallons (151 million liters) of drinking water had been transported.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Shelter options were bleak for Tokyo Prefecture's 1.55 million homeless.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Nearly 800,000 people left Tokyo or Yokohama, first on foot and later via restricted rail service (from 11 September), to stay with relatives or friends elsewhere.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] About 250,000 people dispersed to other parts of Japan, including 17,704 to Kobe, 7,600 to Hokkaidō, and some even to Japan's colonies like Taiwan and Karafuto.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Those remaining in Tokyo flooded large open spaces such as Hibiya Park, Ueno Park, and the Imperial Palace grounds.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] On 9 September, municipal authorities began constructing temporary barracks.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Meiji Shrine site housed nearly 6,000 refugees, Ueno Park over 9,500, and Hibiya Park 7,000.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Many of these open spaces became shantytowns.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Barracks were often cramped, with an average of 0.6 *tsubo* (about 2 square meters (22 sq ft)) of floor space per person.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Sanitation was a major problem, with makeshift latrines overflowing.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] While a modest number of refugees left barrack housing by the end of 1923, many more returned to the disaster zone and erected private makeshift shacks.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] By October 1923, 539,450 people were living in 111,791 such temporary abodes.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Government officials and media outlets made concerted efforts to construct the Great Kantō Earthquake as an unprecedented national calamity, requiring a unified national response.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Newspapers, the chief medium for disseminating news, played a lead role.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Major papers like the *Tokyo Nichi Nichi Shinbun*, *Osaka Asahi Shinbun*, and *Osaka Mainichi Shinbun* used emotive headlines, harrowing survivor accounts, vivid photographs, and even documentary motion pictures to convey the disaster's horror and scale to a national audience.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] These portrayals often framed the disaster in terms of wartime analogies, emphasizing themes of sacrifice and national unity.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The forty-ninth-day memorial service held on 19 October 1923, at the site of the Honjo Clothing Depot, attended by over 200,000 people and leading politicians, was a meticulously choreographed event.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Speeches by figures like Gizō Kasuya and Shōzaburō Horie explicitly linked the victims' sacrifices to the future reconstruction of Tokyo and Japan, urging national unity and effort.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Visual culture, including lithographic prints and postcards, also played a significant role in disseminating the image of a devastated but resilient capital, and of a concerned government responding to the crisis.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Postcards depicting dead bodies, while sometimes classified as contraband, were widespread and brought the human cost of the disaster to a national audience in a stark manner.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] A widespread interpretation, embraced by numerous elites across various sectors of society, was that the earthquake was an act of divine punishment (*tenken* or *tenbatsu*) or heavenly warning.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] This view was not confined to religious leaders but was articulated by bureaucrats, politicians, academics, and social commentators.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster was seen as a response to Japan's perceived moral decline, materialism, luxury-mindedness, hedonism, and excessive individualism that had become prominent since World War I.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The entertainment districts of Tokyo, such as Asakusa, and centers of consumer spending, like the Ginza, were often singled out as epicenters of this perceived degeneracy and thus seen as specifically targeted by the heavens.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The destruction of icons of modern consumerism, such as the Mitsukoshi Department Store and the twelve-story Ryōunkaku tower in Asakusa, was imbued with symbolic meaning.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] This interpretation served as a cosmological bolster for critiques of contemporary society and legitimated calls for social, moral, and ideological reform.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake was thus framed as a moral wake-up call, placing Japan at a crossroads between decline and renovation.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The interpretation of the earthquake as divine admonishment fueled calls for national spiritual renewal (*seishin fukkō*) and economic moderation.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] An Imperial Rescript Regarding the Invigoration of the National Spirit, issued on 10 November 1923, became a foundational document for this movement.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] It urged Japanese people to reject frivolousness, extravagance, and extreme tendencies, and to embrace simplicity, sincerity, fortitude, diligence, thrift, moderation, loyalty, and filial piety.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Government campaigns, such as the 1924 Campaign for the Encouragement of Diligence and Thrift (*Kinken shōrei undō*), employed the memory of the earthquake to promote austerity and national savings.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Policies like the 1924 luxury tariff, which placed a 100 percent duty on a wide range of imported goods deemed luxuries, aimed to curb consumer spending and foster economic self-discipline.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] While these measures had mixed results in altering consumer behavior in the long term, they reflected a broader elite concern with reorienting Japanese society towards more traditional and disciplined values.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The push for spiritual renewal also involved using schools, neighborhood associations, and new media like film and radio to inculcate desired moral values.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The devastation of Tokyo unleashed a wave of optimism among many bureaucrats, urban planners, and social reformers, who saw an unparalleled opportunity to rebuild the city as a modern, rational, and resilient metropolis.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Figures like Gotō Shinpei, Abe Isoo, and Fukuda Tokuzō argued that "old Tokyo" had been a breeding ground for social ills due to overcrowding, poor sanitation, poverty, and inadequate infrastructure.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake, they believed, created a chance to rectify these problems and construct a capital that would reflect new social values and assist the state in managing its subjects.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disorientation and destruction offered a "free field" for new ideas, but reconstruction under Gotō's direction was swift.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Many visions for the new Tokyo were influenced by "authoritarian high modernism," emphasizing state-led planning, technical and scientific progress, and intervention in many aspects of human life, from public health and housing to urban layout and transportation.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Plans called for wider, paved streets, extensive green belts and parks, modern public housing, new sanitation systems, and improved transportation networks.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Some, like Gotō Shinpei, envisioned a grand imperial capital that would project Japan's emerging power and prestige on the international stage, hoping to create a city that matched Paris and Berlin.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Despite the initial optimism, reconstruction planning was fraught with political contestation.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Gotō Shinpei, as Home Minister and head of the Reconstruction Institute (*Teito fukkōin*), championed ambitious and expensive plans, initially proposing a budget of ¥3 billion—more than twice the entire national budget at the time.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] This was met with immediate opposition from Finance Minister Inoue Junnosuke and other cabinet colleagues, who were concerned about the nation's financial stability and favored a more fiscally conservative approach.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Debates raged over the scope of reconstruction, the extent of land readjustment, the design of new infrastructure, and, crucially, the budget.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Imperial Capital Reconstruction Deliberative Council (*Teito fukkō shingikai*), an advisory body of elder statesmen and party leaders, became the site of fierce opposition.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Critics, led by Itō Miyoji, argued the plans were extravagant, could lead to financial collapse, and violated constitutional rights to ownership.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The political infighting exposed deep divisions within Japan's elite and the structural weaknesses of its quasi-democratic, bureaucratic-oligarchic political system.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Gotō's plans were progressively scaled back, with the budget reduced to ¥597 million by the council and further to ¥468 million by the Diet in December 1923.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] A key component of the physical reconstruction was land readjustment (*kukaku seiri*).
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Special Urban Planning Law of December 1923 empowered the government to rationalize irregular land plots, widen streets, and create public spaces by confiscating up to 10 percent of private land without monetary compensation.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Roughly 30,000,000 square meters (320,000,000 sq ft) of land in Tokyo were divided into 66 readjustment districts.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] While the process aimed to create a more rational and user-friendly urban environment, it was met with confusion, resistance, and numerous petitions from landowners and tenants.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Concerns involved the constitutionality of uncompensated land confiscation, the impact on businesses, the rights of tenants, and the adequacy of compensation for relocated structures.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Despite these local-level disputes, the program resulted in the rationalization of many neighborhoods, particularly in eastern Tokyo, and the creation of significant new public land for roads and other infrastructure.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Overall, about 15.3 percent of residential land in readjustment areas was converted to public use, with landowners compensated for acquisitions beyond the 10 percent threshold.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] By the time reconstruction was officially celebrated in March 1930, Tokyo had undergone significant physical changes.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The most notable successes were in transportation infrastructure.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The total area of roads in Tokyo increased by 45 percent, and many were widened and paved, with modern sidewalks.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Key arterial roads like Shōwa-dōri and Yasukuni-dōri were constructed, and new, modern steel bridges, such as the Eitai-bashi and Kiyosu-bashi spanning the Sumida River, became icons of the new city.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The river and canal system was also improved.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] However, many of the more ambitious social and environmental goals were not fully realized.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Spending on parks and green spaces, while resulting in three new large parks and 52 smaller ones, was limited.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Social welfare facilities, while improved, also received a small fraction of the reconstruction budget.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Many of the pre-earthquake urban vulnerabilities and social problems, including slum areas, persisted or re-emerged.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The final reconstruction expenditure by national and city governments totaled roughly ¥744 million.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The site of the Honjo Clothing Depot, where tens of thousands perished, became a focal point for mourning and remembrance.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Plans for a memorial were initiated soon after the disaster.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] In June 1924, the Taishō Earthquake Disaster Memorial Project Association was formed to oversee the project.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] A national design competition for the memorial complex was launched in December 1924.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The winning entry by engineer-architect Maeda Kenjirō, a 53-meter (174 ft) tower, proved controversial due to its perceived resemblance to a Prussian triumphal tower and its perceived insensitivity to Buddhist sensibilities.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] After sustained protest, particularly from Buddhist federations, the design was scrapped in December 1926.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Engineer Itō Chūta was then appointed to create a new, more "Japanese" design, heavily influenced by Buddhist architecture, featuring a pagoda that would house a charnel house.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Earthquake Memorial Hall (later the Tokyo Metropolitan Memorial Hall) in Yokoamichō Park was completed on 1 September 1930.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Great Kantō Earthquake left an indelible mark on Japan.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] 1 September was designated as Disaster Prevention Day (防災の日, *Bōsai no hi*) in 1960, an annual commemoration involving nationwide disaster drills and awareness campaigns.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster highlighted urban vulnerabilities and influenced subsequent approaches to city planning and building codes, although the ideal of a truly disaster-proof city remained elusive.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The memory of the earthquake, particularly the firestorms and the Honjo Clothing Depot tragedy, continued to haunt Tokyoites, influencing their behavior even during the World War II bombings.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The events of 1923 also served as a catalyst for long-term government efforts to foster neighborhood associations (*tonarigumi*) and promote civil defense, trends that intensified in the 1930s and during the war.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disorientation and destruction caused by the disaster marked a "significant divide" in the "massification" of culture, consumption, and taste, accelerating social and cultural changes and providing a "free field" for new artistic and radical movements.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The center of urban life in Tokyo also shifted, as the old merchant quarters of the *shitamachi* ("Low City") were particularly devastated, pushing development toward the more residential "High City" (*yamanote*).
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Despite the significant scaling-back of Gotō Shinpei's original vision, the reconstruction provided a fine example of creative recovery, rebuilding Tokyo as a modern city and serving as a model for urban development throughout Japan until the end of World War II.
[src:honshu/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake and its aftermath remain a subject of historical study and public memory, serving as a stark reminder of Japan's seismic activity and the complex interplay of disaster, society, and national identity.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] On 11 March 2011, at 14:46:24 JST (05:46:24 UTC), a Mw 9.0–9.1 undersea megathrust earthquake occurred in the Pacific Ocean, 72 km (45 mi) east of the Oshika Peninsula of the Tōhoku region of Japan.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It lasted approximately six minutes and caused a tsunami.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It is sometimes known in Japan as the "**Great East Japan Earthquake**" (東日本大震災, *Higashi Nihon Daishinsai*), among other names.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It is often referred to by its numerical date, **3.11** (read *San ten Ichi-ichi* in Japanese).
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The earthquake was the most powerful ever recorded in Japan, and the fourth most powerful recorded in the world since modern seismography began in 1900.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It triggered powerful tsunami waves that may have reached heights of up to 40.5 meters (133 ft) in Miyako in Tōhoku's Iwate Prefecture, and which, in the Sendai area, traveled at 700 km/h (435 mph) and up to 10 km (6 mi) inland.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Residents of Sendai had only eight to ten minutes of warning, and more than a hundred evacuation sites were washed away.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The snowfall which accompanied the tsunami and the freezing temperature hindered rescue works; for instance, in Ishinomaki, the city with the most deaths, the temperature was 0 °C (32 °F) as the tsunami hit.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Official figures released in 2021 reported 19,759 deaths, 6,242 injured, 284 firefighters dead from attempts to close preventative fire gates, and 2,553 missing.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A report in 2015 found that 228,863 people were still living away from their home either temporarily or permanently.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami caused the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster, primarily the meltdowns of three of its reactors, the discharge of radioactive water in Fukushima and the associated evacuation zones affecting hundreds of thousands of residents.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Many electrical generators ran out of fuel.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The loss of electrical power halted cooling systems, causing heat to build.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Without ventilation, hydrogen gas accumulated within the upper refueling hall and exploded, forcefully ejecting the refueling hall's blast panels.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Residents within a 20 km (12 mi) radius of the Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant and a 10 km (6.2 mi) radius of the Fukushima Daini Nuclear Power Plant were evacuated.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Early estimates placed insured losses from the earthquake alone at US$14.5 to $34.6 billion.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Bank of Japan offered ¥15 trillion (US$183 billion) to the banking system on 14 March 2011 in an effort to normalize market conditions.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The estimated economic damage amounted to over $300 billion, making it the costliest natural disaster in history.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] According to a 2020 study, "the earthquake and its aftermaths resulted in a 0.47 percentage point decline in Japan's real GDP growth in the year following the disaster".
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The earthquake was initially reported as 7.9 Mw by the USGS before it was quickly upgraded to 8.8 Mw, then to 8.9 Mw, and then finally to 9.0 Mw.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] On 11 July 2016, the USGS further upgraded the earthquake to 9.1.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Sendai was the nearest major city to the earthquake, 130 km (81 mi) from the epicenter; the earthquake occurred 373 km (232 mi) northeast of Tokyo.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The main earthquake was preceded by a number of large foreshocks, with hundreds of aftershocks reported.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] One of the first major foreshocks was a 7.2 Mw event on 9 March, approximately 40 km (25 mi) from the epicenter of the 11 March earthquake, with another three on the same day in excess of 6.0 Mw.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Following the main earthquake on 11 March, a 7.4 Mw aftershock was reported at 15:08 JST (6:06 UTC), succeeded by a 7.9 Mw at 15:15 JST (6:16 UTC) and a 7.7 Mw at 15:26 JST (6:26 UTC).
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Over 800 aftershocks of magnitude 4.5 Mw or greater occurred after the initial quake.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Aftershocks followed Omori's law, which states that the rate of aftershocks declines with the reciprocal of the time since the main quake.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The aftershocks thus tapered off over time, but continued for years after the initial quake, including one on 26 October 2013 (local time) of magnitude 7.1 Mw.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Initially, the earthquake caused part of Honshu's Pacific coast to sink by roughly a meter, but after about three years, the coast rose back and then kept on rising to exceed its original height.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This megathrust earthquake was a recurrence of the mechanism of the earlier 869 Sanriku earthquake, which has been estimated as having a magnitude of at least 8.4 Mw, which also created a large tsunami that inundated the Sendai plain.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Three tsunami deposits have been identified within the Holocene sequence of the plain, all formed within the last 3,000 years, suggesting an 800 to 1,100 year recurrence interval for large tsunamigenic earthquakes.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In 2001 it was reckoned that there was a high likelihood of a large tsunami hitting the Sendai plain as more than 1,100 years had then elapsed.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In 2007, the probability of an earthquake with a magnitude of Mw 8.1–8.3 was estimated as 99% within the following 30 years.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This earthquake occurred where the Pacific plate is subducting under the plate beneath northern Honshu.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Pacific plate, which moves at a rate of 8 to 9 cm (3.1 to 3.5 in) per year, dips under Honshu's underlying plate, building large amounts of elastic energy.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This motion pushes the upper plate down until the accumulated stress causes a seismic slip-rupture event.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The break caused the sea floor to rise by several meters.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The magnitude of this earthquake was a surprise to some seismologists.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A quake of this magnitude usually has a rupture length of at least 500 km (310 mi) and generally requires a long, relatively straight fault surface.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Because the plate boundary and subduction zone in the area of the Honshu rupture is not very straight, it is unusual for the magnitude of its earthquake to exceed 8.5 Mw.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The hypocentral region of this earthquake extended from offshore Iwate Prefecture to offshore Ibaraki Prefecture.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Japan Meteorological Agency said that the earthquake may have ruptured the fault zone from Iwate to Ibaraki with a length of 500 km (310 mi) and a width of 200 km (120 mi).
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Analysis showed that this earthquake consisted of a set of three events.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Other major earthquakes with tsunamis struck the Sanriku Coast region in 1896 and in 1933.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The source area of this earthquake has a relatively high coupling coefficient surrounded by areas of relatively low coupling coefficients in the west, north, and south.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The seismic moment of this earthquake accounts for about 93% of the estimated cumulative moment from 1926 to March 2011.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Hence, earthquakes in this area with magnitudes of about 7 since 1926 had only released part of the accumulated energy.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In the area near the trench, the coupling coefficient is high, which could act as the source of the large tsunami.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Most of the foreshocks are interplate earthquakes with thrust-type focal mechanisms.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Both interplate and intraplate earthquakes appeared in the aftershocks offshore Sanriku coast with considerable proportions.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The surface energy of the seismic waves from the earthquake was calculated to be 1.9×1017 joules, which is nearly double that of the 9.1 Mw 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami that killed 230,000 people.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] If harnessed, the seismic energy from this earthquake would power a city the size of Los Angeles for an entire year.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The seismic moment (M0), which represents a physical size for the event, was calculated by the USGS at 3.9×1022 joules, slightly less than the 2004 Indian Ocean quake.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The strong ground motion registered at the maximum of *Shindo* 7 on the Japan Meteorological Agency seismic intensity scale in Kurihara, Miyagi Prefecture.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Three other prefectures—Fukushima, Ibaraki and Tochigi—recorded a 6 upper on the JMA scale.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Seismic stations in Iwate, Gunma, Saitama and Chiba Prefectures measured a 6 lower, while Tokyo and five other prefectures recorded 5 upper.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Japan's National Research Institute for Earth Science and Disaster Prevention (NIED) calculated a peak ground acceleration of 2.99 *g* (29.33 m/s2).
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Tremors from the earthquake were also felt in the Northern Mariana Islands, the Korean Peninsula, Taiwan, Northeast China and the Russian Far East.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Portions of northeastern Japan shifted by as much as 2.4 meters (7 ft 10 in) closer to North America, making some sections of Japan's landmass wider than before.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Those areas of Japan closest to the epicenter experienced the largest shifts.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A 400-kilometer (250 mi) stretch of coastline dropped vertically by 0.6 meters (2 ft 0 in), allowing the tsunami to travel farther and faster onto land.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] One early estimate suggested that the Pacific plate may have moved westward by up to 20 meters (66 ft), and another early estimate put the amount of slippage at as much as 40 m (130 ft).
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] On 6 April, the Japanese coast guard said that the quake shifted the seabed near the epicenter 24 meters (79 ft) and elevated the seabed off the coast of Miyagi Prefecture by 3 meters (9.8 ft).
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A report by the Japan Agency for Marine-Earth Science and Technology, published in *Science* on 2 December 2011, concluded that the seabed in the area between the epicenter and the Japan Trench moved 50 meters (160 ft) east-southeast and rose about 7 meters (23 ft) as a result of the quake.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The report also stated that the quake had caused several major landslides on the seabed in the affected area.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Earth's axis shifted by estimates of between 10 and 25 cm (4 and 10 in).
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This deviation led to a number of small planetary changes, including the length of a day, the tilt of the Earth, and the Chandler wobble.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The speed of the Earth's rotation increased, shortening the day by 1.8 microseconds due to the redistribution of Earth's mass.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The axial shift was caused by the redistribution of mass on the Earth's surface, which changed the planet's moment of inertia.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Because of conservation of angular momentum, such changes of inertia result in small changes to the Earth's rate of rotation.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] These are expected changes for an earthquake of this magnitude.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The earthquake also generated infrasound waves detected by perturbations in the orbit of the GOCE satellite, which thus serendipitously became the first seismograph in orbit.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Following the earthquake, cracks were observed to have formed in the roof of Mount Fuji's magma chamber.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Seiches observed in Sognefjorden, Norway, were attributed to distant S waves and Love waves generated by the earthquake.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] These seiches began to occur roughly half an hour after the main shock hit Japan, and continued to occur for 3 hours, during which waves of up to 1.5 meters high were observed.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Soil liquefaction was evident in areas of reclaimed land around Tokyo, particularly in Urayasu, Chiba City, Funabashi, Narashino (all in Chiba Prefecture) and in the Koto, Edogawa, Minato, Chūō, and Ōta wards of Tokyo.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Approximately 30 homes or buildings were destroyed and 1,046 other buildings were damaged to varying degrees.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Nearby Haneda Airport, built mostly on reclaimed land, was not damaged.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Odaiba also experienced liquefaction, but damage was minimal.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Shinmoedake, a volcano in Kyushu, erupted three days after the earthquake.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The volcano had previously erupted in January 2011; it is not known if the later eruption was linked to the earthquake.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In Antarctica, the seismic waves from the earthquake were reported to have caused the Whillans Ice Stream to slip by about 0.5 meters (1 ft 8 in).
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The first sign international researchers had that the earthquake caused such a dramatic change in the Earth's rotation came from the United States Geological Survey which monitors Global Positioning Satellite (GPS) stations across the world.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Survey team had several GPS monitors located near the scene of the earthquake.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The GPS station located nearest the epicenter moved almost 4 m (13 ft).
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This motivated government researchers to look into other ways the earthquake may have had large scale effects on the planet.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Calculations at NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory determined that the Earth's rotation was changed by the earthquake to the point where the days are now 1.8 microseconds shorter.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Japan experienced over 1,000 aftershocks since the earthquake, with 80 registering over magnitude 6.0 Mw and several of which have been over magnitude 7.0 Mw.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A month later, a major aftershock struck offshore on 7 April with a magnitude of 7.1 Mw.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Its epicenter was underwater, 66 km (41 mi) off the coast of Sendai.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Japan Meteorological Agency assigned a magnitude of 7.4 MJMA, while the United States Geological Survey lowered it to 7.1 Mw.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] At least four people were killed, and electricity was cut off across much of northern Japan including the loss of external power to Higashidōri Nuclear Power Plant and Rokkasho Reprocessing Plant.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Four days later on 11 April, another magnitude 7.1 Mw aftershock struck Fukushima, causing additional damage and killing a total of three people.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] On 7 December 2012 a large aftershock of magnitude 7.3 Mw caused a minor tsunami, and again on 26 October 2013 a small tsunami was recorded after a 7.1 Mw aftershock.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] As of 16 March 2012 aftershocks continued, totaling 1887 events over magnitude 4.0; a regularly updated map showing all shocks of magnitude 4.5 and above near or off the east coast of Honshu in the last seven days showed over 20 events.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] As of 11 March 2016 there had been 869 aftershocks of 5.0 Mw or greater, 118 of 6.0 Mw or greater, and 9 over 7.0 Mw as reported by the Japan Meteorological Agency.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The number of aftershocks was associated with decreased health across Japan.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] On 13 February 2021, a magnitude 7.1–7.3 earthquake struck off the coast of Sendai.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It caused some damage in Miyagi and Fukushima prefectures.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] One person was killed, and 185 were injured.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Geospatial Information Authority of Japan reported land subsidence based on the height of triangulation stations in the area measured by GPS as compared to their previous values from 14 April 2011.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Scientists say that the subsidence is permanent.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] As a result, the communities in question are now more susceptible to flooding during high tides.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] One minute before the earthquake was felt in Tokyo, the Earthquake Early Warning system, which includes more than 1,000 seismometers in Japan, sent out warnings of impending strong shaking to millions.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It is believed that the early warning by the Japan Meteorological Agency (JMA) saved many lives.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The warning for the general public was delivered about eight seconds after the first P wave was detected, or about 31 seconds after the earthquake occurred.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] However, the estimated intensities were smaller than the actual ones in some places, especially in Kanto, Koshinetsu, and Northern Tōhoku regions where the populace warning did not trigger.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] There were also cases where large differences between estimated intensities by the Earthquake Early Warning system and the actual intensities occurred in the aftershocks and triggered earthquakes.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Such discrepancies in the warning were attributed by the JMA to the system's inability to distinguish between two different earthquakes that happened at around same time, as well as to the reduced number of reporting seismometers due to power outages and connection failures.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The system's software was subsequently modified to handle this kind of situation.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] An upthrust of 6 to 8 meters (20 to 26 ft) along a 180-kilometer (110 mi)-wide seabed at 60 kilometers (37 mi) offshore from the east coast of Tōhoku resulted in a major tsunami that brought destruction along the Pacific coastline of Japan's northern islands.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Thousands of people died and entire towns were devastated.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami propagated throughout the Pacific Ocean region reaching the entire Pacific coast of North and South America from Alaska to Chile.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Warnings were issued and evacuations were carried out in many countries bordering the Pacific.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Although the tsunami affected many of these places, the heights of the waves were minor.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Chile's Pacific coast, one of the farthest from Japan at about 17,000 kilometers (11,000 mi) away, was struck by waves 2 meters (6.6 ft) high, compared with an estimated wave height of 38.9 meters (128 ft) at Omoe peninsula, Miyako city, Japan.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami warning issued by the Japan Meteorological Agency was the most serious on its warning scale; it was rated as a "major tsunami", being at least 3 meters (9.8 ft) high.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The actual height prediction varied, the greatest being for Miyagi at 6 meters (20 ft) high.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami inundated a total area of approximately 561 square kilometers (217 sq mi) in Japan.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] At 15:55 JST, a tsunami was observed flooding Sendai Airport, which is located near the coast of Miyagi Prefecture, with waves sweeping away cars and planes and flooding various buildings as they traveled inland.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The impact of the tsunami in and around Sendai Airport was filmed by an NHK News helicopter, showing a number of vehicles on local roads trying to escape the approaching wave and being engulfed by it.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A 4-meter-high (13 ft) tsunami hit Iwate Prefecture.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Wakabayashi Ward in Sendai was also particularly hard hit.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] At least 101 designated tsunami evacuation sites were hit by the wave.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Like the 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami, the damage by surging water, though much more localized, was far more deadly and destructive than the actual quake.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Entire towns were destroyed in tsunami-hit areas in Japan, including 9,500 missing in Minamisanriku; one thousand bodies had been recovered in the town by 14 March 2011.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Among the factors in the high death toll was the unexpectedly large water surge.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The sea walls in several cities had been built to protect against tsunamis of much lower heights.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Also, many people caught in the tsunami thought they were on high enough ground to be safe.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] According to a special committee on disaster prevention designated by the Japanese government, the tsunami protection policy had been intended to deal with only tsunamis that had been scientifically proved to occur repeatedly.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The committee advised that future policy should be to protect against the highest possible tsunami.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Because tsunami walls had been overtopped, the committee also suggested, besides building taller tsunami walls, also teaching citizens how to evacuate if a large-scale tsunami should strike.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Large parts of Kuji and the southern section of Ōfunato including the port area were almost entirely destroyed.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Also largely destroyed was Rikuzentakata, where the tsunami was three stories high.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Other cities destroyed or heavily damaged by the tsunami include Kamaishi, Miyako, Ōtsuchi, and Yamada (in Iwate Prefecture), Namie, Sōma, and Minamisōma (in Fukushima Prefecture) and Shichigahama, Higashimatsushima, Onagawa, Natori, Ishinomaki, and Kesennuma (in Miyagi Prefecture).
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The most severe effects of the tsunami were felt along a 670-kilometer-long (420 mi) stretch of coastline from Erimo, Hokkaido, in the north to Ōarai, Ibaraki, in the south, with most of the destruction in that area occurring in the hour following the earthquake.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Near Ōarai, people captured images of a huge whirlpool that had been generated by the tsunami.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami washed away the sole bridge to Miyatojima, Miyagi, isolating the island's 900 residents.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A 2 meters (6 ft 7 in) high tsunami hit Chiba Prefecture about 2+1⁄2 hours after the quake, causing heavy damage to cities such as Asahi.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] On 13 March 2011, the Japan Meteorological Agency (JMA) published details of tsunami observations recorded around the coastline of Japan following the earthquake.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The bulletin also included initial tsunami observation details, as well as more detailed maps for the coastlines affected by the tsunami waves.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami at Ryōri Bay (綾里湾), Ōfunato reached a height of 40.1 meters (132 ft) (run-up elevation).
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Fishing equipment was scattered on the high cliff above the bay.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] At Tarō, Iwate, the tsunami reached a height of 37.9 meters (124 ft) up the slope of a mountain some 200 meters (660 ft) away from the coastline.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Also, at the slope of a nearby mountain from 400 meters (1,300 ft) away at Aneyoshi fishery port (姉吉漁港) of Omoe peninsula (重茂半島) in Miyako, Iwate, Tokyo University of Marine Science and Technology found estimated tsunami run up height of 38.9 meters (128 ft).
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This height is deemed the record in Japan historically, as of reporting date, that exceeds 38.2 meters (125 ft) from the 1896 Sanriku earthquake.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It was also estimated that the tsunami reached heights of up to 40.5 meters (133 ft) in Miyako in Tōhoku's Iwate Prefecture.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The inundated areas closely matched those of the 869 Sanriku tsunami.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Inundation heights were observed along 2,000 kilometers (1,200 mi) of the coast from Hokkaido to Kyushu in a 2012 study.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Maximum run-up heights greater than 10 meters (33 ft) were distributed along 530 kilometers (330 mi) of coast, and maximum run-up heights greater than 20 meters (66 ft) were distributed along 200 kilometers (120 mi) of the coast, measured directly.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami resulted in significant erosion of the Rikuzen-Takata coastline, mainly caused by backwash.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A 2016 study indicated that the coast has not naturally recovered at a desirable rate since the tsunami.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A Japanese government study found that 58% of people in coastal areas in Iwate, Miyagi, and Fukushima prefectures heeded tsunami warnings immediately after the quake and headed for higher ground.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Of those who attempted to evacuate after hearing the warning, only five percent were caught in the tsunami.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Of those who did not heed the warning, 49% were hit by the water.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Delayed evacuations in response to the warnings had a number of causes.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami height that had been initially predicted by the tsunami warning system was lower than the actual tsunami height; this error contributed to the delayed escape of some residents.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The discrepancy arose as follows: in order to produce a quick prediction of a tsunami's height and thus to provide a timely warning, the initial earthquake and tsunami warning that was issued for the event was based on a calculation that requires only about three minutes.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This calculation is, in turn, based on the maximum amplitude of the seismic wave.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The amplitude of the seismic wave is measured using the JMA magnitude scale, which is similar to Richter scale.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] However, these scales "saturate" for earthquakes that are above a certain magnitude (magnitude 8 on the JMA scale); that is, in the case of very large earthquakes, the scales' values change little despite large differences in the earthquakes' energy.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This resulted in an underestimation of the tsunami's height in initial reports.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Problems in issuing updates also contributed to delays in evacuations.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The warning system was supposed to be updated about 15 minutes after the earthquake occurred, by which time the calculation for the moment magnitude scale would normally be completed.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] However, the strong quake had exceeded the measurement limit of all of the teleseismometers within Japan, and thus it was impossible to calculate the moment magnitude based on data from those seismometers.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Another cause of delayed evacuations was the release of the second update on the tsunami warning long after the earthquake (28 minutes, according to observations); by that time, power failures and similar circumstances reportedly prevented the update from reaching some residents.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Also, observed data from tidal meters that were located off the coast were not fully reflected in the second warning.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In response to the aforementioned shortcomings in the tsunami warning system, JMA began an investigation in 2011 and updated their system in 2013.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In the updated system, for a powerful earthquake that is capable of causing the JMA magnitude scale to saturate, no quantitative prediction will be released in the initial warning; instead, there will be words that describe the situation's emergency.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] There are plans to install new teleseismometers with the ability to measure larger earthquakes, which would allow the calculation of a quake's moment magnitude scale in a timely manner.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] JMA also implemented a simpler empirical method to integrate, into a tsunami warning, data from GPS tidal meters as well as from undersea water pressure meters, and there are plans to install more of these meters and to develop further technology to utilize data observed by them.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] To prevent under-reporting of tsunami heights, early quantitative observation data that are smaller than the expected amplitude will be overridden and the public will instead be told that the situation is under observation.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] About 90 seconds after an earthquake, an additional report on the possibility of a tsunami will also be included in observation reports, in order to warn people before the JMA magnitude can be calculated.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Pacific Tsunami Warning Center (PTWC) in Hawaii issued tsunami watches and announcements for locations in the Pacific.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] At 07:30 UTC, PTWC issued a widespread tsunami warning covering the entire Pacific Ocean.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Russia evacuated 11,000 residents from coastal areas of the Kuril Islands.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The United States National Tsunami Warning Center issued a tsunami warning for the coastal areas in most of California, all of Oregon, and the western part of Alaska, and a tsunami advisory covering the Pacific coastlines of most of Alaska, and all of Washington and British Columbia, Canada.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In California and Oregon, up to 2.4 m-high (7.9 ft) tsunami waves hit some areas, damaging docks and harbors and causing over US$10 million in damage.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In Curry County, Oregon, US$7 million in damage occurred including the destruction of 1,100 m (3,600 ft) of docks at the Brookings harbor; the county received over US$1 million in FEMA emergency grants from the US Federal Government.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Surges of up to 1 m (3 ft 3 in) hit Vancouver Island in Canada prompting some evacuations, and causing boats to be banned from the waters surrounding the island for 12 hours following the wave strike, leaving many island residents in the area without means of getting to work.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In the Philippines, waves up to 0.5 m (1 ft 8 in) high hit the eastern seaboard of the country.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Some houses along the coast in Jayapura, Indonesia were destroyed.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Authorities in Wewak, East Sepik, Papua New Guinea evacuated 100 patients from the city's Boram Hospital before it was hit by waves, causing an estimated US$4 million in damage.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Hawaii estimated damage to public infrastructure alone at US$3 million, with damage to private properties, including resort hotels such as Four Seasons Resort Hualalai, estimated at tens of millions of dollars.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It was reported that a 1.5 m-high (4.9 ft) wave completely submerged Midway Atoll's reef inlets and Spit Island, killing more than 110,000 nesting seabirds at the Midway Atoll National Wildlife Refuge.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Some other South Pacific countries, including Tonga and New Zealand, and US territories American Samoa and Guam, experienced larger-than-normal waves, but did not report any major damage.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] However, in Guam some roads were closed off and people were evacuated from low-lying areas.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Along the Pacific Coast of Mexico and South America, tsunami surges were reported, but in most places caused little or no damage.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Peru reported a wave of 1.5 m (4 ft 11 in) and more than 300 homes damaged.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The surge in Chile was large enough to damage more than 200 houses, with waves of up to 3 m (9.8 ft).
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In the Galápagos Islands, 260 families received assistance following a 3 m (9.8 ft) surge which arrived 20 hours after the earthquake, after the tsunami warning had been lifted.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] There was a great deal of damage to buildings on the islands and one man was injured but there were no reported fatalities.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami broke icebergs off the Sulzberger Ice Shelf in Antarctica, 13,000 km (8,100 mi) away.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The main iceberg measured 9.5 km × 6.5 km (5.9 mi × 4.0 mi) (approximately the area of Manhattan Island) and about 80 m (260 ft) thick.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A total of 125 km2 (48 sq mi; 31,000 acres) of ice broke away.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] As of April 2012, wreckage from the tsunami spread around the world, including a soccer ball which was found in Alaska's Middleton Island and a Japanese motorcycle found in British Columbia, Canada.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] On the day of the earthquake, the waters of several fjords across Norway appeared to seethe as if boiling, and formed waves that rolled onto shores, most prominently in Sognefjorden, where the phenomenon was caught on film.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] After two years of research into the incidents in Norway, scientists concluded that the seismic energy of the earthquake generated seiche waves thousands of kilometers away.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The official figures released in 2021 reported 19,759 deaths, 6,242 injured, and 2,553 missing.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] There were 10,567 deaths in Miyagi, 5,145 in Iwate, 3,920 in Fukushima, 66 in Ibaraki, 22 in Chiba, eight in Tokyo, six in Kanagawa, four in Tochigi, three each in Aomori and Yamagata, and one each in Gunma, Saitama and Hokkaido.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The leading causes of death were drowning (90.64% or 14,308 bodies), burning (0.9% or 145 bodies) and others (4.2% or 667 bodies, mostly crushed by heavy objects).
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Injuries related to nuclear exposure or the discharge of radioactive water in Fukushima are difficult to trace as 60% of the 20,000 workers on-site declined to participate in state-sponsored free health checks.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Elderly aged over 60 account for 65.8% of all deaths, as shown on the table to the right.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A few cases of suicide are also included.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Most of these deaths occurred during the first six months after the earthquake and the number dropped thereafter, but as time has passed, the number has continued to increase.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Most of these deaths occurred in Fukushima Prefecture, where the prefectural government has suggested that they could be due to evacuations caused by the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Within Fukushima Prefecture, these indirect casualties have already resulted in more deaths than the number of people killed directly by earthquake and tsunami.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Save the Children reports that as many as 100,000 children were uprooted from their homes, some of whom were separated from their families because the earthquake occurred during the school day.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] 236 children were orphaned in the prefectures of Iwate, Miyagi and Fukushima by the disaster; 1,580 children lost either one or both parents, 846 in Miyagi, 572 in Iwate, and 162 in Fukushima.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The quake and tsunami killed 378 elementary, middle-school, and high school students and left 158 others missing.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] One elementary school in Ishinomaki, Miyagi, Okawa Elementary School, lost 74 of 108 students and 10 of 13 teachers in the tsunami due to poor decision making in evacuation.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The Japanese Foreign Ministry confirmed the deaths of nineteen foreigners.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Among them were two English teachers from the United States affiliated with the Japan Exchange and Teaching Program; a Canadian missionary in Shiogama; and citizens of China, North and South Korea, Taiwan, Pakistan and the Philippines.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] By 9:30 UTC on 11 March 2011, Google Person Finder, which was previously used in the Haitian, Chilean, and Christchurch, New Zealand earthquakes, was collecting information about survivors and their locations.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Japanese funerals are normally elaborate Buddhist ceremonies that entail cremation.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The thousands of bodies, however, exceeded the capacity of available crematoriums and morgues, many of them damaged, and there were shortages of both kerosene—each cremation requires 50 litres—and dry ice for preservation.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The single crematorium in Higashimatsushima, for example, could only handle four bodies a day, although hundreds were found there.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Governments and the military were forced to bury many bodies in hastily dug mass graves with rudimentary or no rites, although relatives of the deceased were promised that they would be cremated later.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] As of 27 May 2011, three Japan Ground Self-Defense Force members had died while conducting relief operations in Tōhoku.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] As of March 2012, the Japanese government had recognized 1,331 deaths as indirectly related to the earthquake, such as caused by harsh living conditions after the disaster.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] As of 30 April 2012, 18 people had died and 420 had been injured while participating in disaster recovery or clean-up efforts.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami was reported to have caused several deaths outside Japan.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] One man was killed in Jayapura, Papua, Indonesia after being swept out to sea.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A man who is said to have been attempting to photograph the oncoming tsunami at the mouth of the Klamath River, south of Crescent City, California, was swept out to sea.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] His body was found on 2 April 2011 along Ocean Beach in Fort Stevens State Park, Oregon, 530 km (330 mi) to the north.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The degree and extent of damage caused by the earthquake and resulting tsunami were enormous, with most of the damage being caused by the tsunami.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Video footage of the towns that were worst affected shows little more than piles of rubble, with almost no parts of any structures left standing.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Estimates of the cost of the damage range well into the tens of billions of US dollars; before-and-after satellite photographs of devastated regions show immense damage.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Although Japan has invested the equivalent of billions of dollars on anti-tsunami seawalls which line at least 40% of its 34,751 km (21,593 mi) coastline and stand up to 12 m (39 ft) high, the tsunami simply washed over the top of some seawalls, collapsing some in the process.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Japan's National Police Agency said on 3 April 2011, that 45,700 buildings were destroyed and 144,300 were damaged by the quake and tsunami.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The damaged buildings included 29,500 structures in Miyagi Prefecture, 12,500 in Iwate Prefecture and 2,400 in Fukushima Prefecture.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Three hundred hospitals with 20 beds or more in Tōhoku were damaged by the disaster, with 11 being completely destroyed.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The earthquake and tsunami created an estimated 24–25 million tons of rubble and debris in Japan.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A report by the National Police Agency of Japan on 10 September 2018 listed 121,778 buildings as "total collapsed", with a further 280,926 buildings "half collapsed", and another 699,180 buildings "partially damaged".
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The earthquake and tsunami also caused extensive and severe structural damage in north-eastern Japan, including heavy damage to roads and railways as well as fires in many areas, and a dam collapse.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Japanese Prime Minister Naoto Kan said, "In the 65 years after the end of World War II, this is the toughest and the most difficult crisis for Japan." Around 4.4 million households in northeastern Japan were left without electricity and 1.5 million without water.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] An estimated 230,000 automobiles and trucks were damaged or destroyed in the disaster.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] As of the end of May 2011, residents of Iwate, Miyagi, and Fukushima prefectures had requested the deregistration of 15,000 vehicles, meaning that the owners of those vehicles were writing them off as unrepairable or unsalvageable.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Low temperature and snowfall were major concerns after the earthquake.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Snow arrived minutes before or after the tsunami, depending on locations.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In Ishinomaki, the city which suffered the most deaths, a temperature of 0 °C (32 °F) was measured, and it began to snow within a couple of hours of the earthquake.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Major snow fell again on 16 March, and intermittently in the coming weeks.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] 18 March was the coldest of that month, recording −4 to 6 °C (25 to 43 °F) in Sendai.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Photos of city ruins covered with snow were featured in various photo albums in international media, including NASA.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami produced huge amounts of debris: estimates of 5 million tonnes of waste were reported by the Japanese Ministry of the Environment.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Some of this waste, mostly plastic and styrofoam, washed up on the coasts of Canada and the United States in late 2011.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Along the west coast of the United States, this increased the amount of litter by a factor of ten and may have transported alien species.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] All of Japan's ports were briefly shut down after the earthquake, though the ones in Tokyo and southwards soon re-opened.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Fifteen ports were located in the disaster zone.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The north eastern ports of Hachinohe, Sendai, Ishinomaki and Onahama were destroyed, while the Port of Chiba (which serves the hydrocarbon industry) and Japan's ninth-largest container port at Kashima were also affected, though less severely.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The ports at Hitachinaka, Hitachi, Soma, Shiogama, Kesennuma, Ofunato, Kamashi and Miyako were also damaged and closed to ships.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] All 15 ports reopened to limited ship traffic by 29 March 2011.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A total of 319 fishing ports, about 10% of Japan's fishing ports, were damaged in the disaster.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Most were restored to operating condition by 18 April 2012.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The Port of Tokyo suffered slight damage; the effects of the quake included visible smoke rising from a building in the port with parts of the port areas being flooded, including soil liquefaction in Tokyo Disneyland's parking lot.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The Fujinuma irrigation dam in Sukagawa ruptured, causing flooding and the washing away of five homes.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Eight people were missing and four bodies were discovered by the morning.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Reportedly, some locals had attempted to repair leaks in the dam before it completely failed.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] On 12 March 252 dams were inspected and it was discovered that six embankment dams had shallow cracks on their crests.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The reservoir at one concrete gravity dam suffered a small non-serious slope failure.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] All damaged dams are functioning with no problems.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Four dams within the quake area were unreachable.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In the immediate aftermath of the calamity, at least 1.5 million households were reported to have lost access to water supplies.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] By 21 March 2011, this number fell to 1.04 million.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] According to the Japanese trade ministry, around 4.4 million households served by Tōhoku Electric Power (TEP) in northeastern Japan were left without electricity.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Several nuclear and conventional power plants went offline, reducing the Tokyo Electric Power Company's (TEPCO) total capacity by 21 GW.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Rolling blackouts began on 14 March due to power shortages caused by the earthquake.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] TEPCO, which normally provides approximately 40 GW of electricity, announced that it could only provide about 30 GW, because 40% of the electricity used in the greater Tokyo area was supplied by reactors in the Niigata and Fukushima prefectures.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The reactors at the Fukushima Daiichi and Fukushima Dai-ni plants were automatically taken offline when the first earthquake occurred and sustained major damage from the earthquake and subsequent tsunami.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Rolling blackouts of approximately three hours were experienced throughout April and May while TEPCO scrambled to find a temporary power solution.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The blackouts affected Tokyo, Kanagawa, Eastern Shizuoka, Yamanashi, Chiba, Ibaraki, Saitama, Tochigi, and Gunma prefectures.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Voluntary reductions in electricity use by consumers in the Kanto area helped reduce the predicted frequency and duration of the blackouts.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] By 21 March 2011, the number of households in the north without electricity fell to 242,927.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Tōhoku Electric Power was not able to provide the Kanto region with additional power because TEP's power plants were also damaged in the earthquake.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Two substations, one in Shizuoka Prefecture and one in Nagano Prefecture, were able to convert between frequencies and transfer electricity from Kansai to Kanto and Tōhoku, but their capacity was limited to 1 GW.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] With damage to so many power plants, it was feared it might be years before a long-term solution could be found.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] To help alleviate the shortage, three steel manufacturers in the Kanto region contributed electricity produced by their in-house conventional power stations to TEPCO for distribution to the general public.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Sumitomo Metal Industries could produce up to 500 MW, JFE Steel 400 MW, and Nippon Steel 500 MW of electric power.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Auto and auto parts makers in Kanto and Tōhoku agreed in May 2011 to operate their factories on Saturdays and Sundays and close on Thursdays and Fridays to help alleviate electricity shortages during the summer of 2011.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The public and other companies were also encouraged to conserve electricity in the 2011 summer months (Setsuden).
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The expected electricity crisis in 2011 summer was successfully prevented thanks to all the *setsuden* measures.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Peak electricity consumption recorded by TEPCO during the period was 49.22GW, which is 10.77GW (18%) lower than the peak consumption in the previous year.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Overall electricity consumption during July and August was also 14% less than in the previous year.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The peak electricity consumption within TEP's area was 12.46GW during the 2011 summer, 3.11GW (20%) less than the peak consumption in the previous year, and the overall consumption have been reduced by 11% in July with 17% in August compared to previous year.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A 220,000-barrel-per-day (35,000 m3) oil refinery of Cosmo Oil Company was set on fire by the quake at Ichihara, Chiba Prefecture, to the east of Tokyo.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] It was extinguished after ten days, injuring six people, and destroying storage tanks.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Other refineries halted production due to safety checks and power loss.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In Sendai, a 145,000-barrel-per-day (23,100 m3) refinery owned by the largest refiner in Japan, JX Nippon Oil & Energy, was also set ablaze by the quake.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Workers were evacuated, but tsunami warnings hindered efforts to extinguish the fire until 14 March, when officials planned to do so.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] An analyst estimated that consumption of various types of oil could have increased by as much as 300,000 barrels (48,000 m3) per day (as well as LNG), as back-up power plants burning fossil fuels attempted to compensate for the loss of 11 GW of Japan's nuclear power capacity.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The city-owned plant for importing liquefied natural gas in Sendai was severely damaged, and supplies were halted for at least a month.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In addition to refining and storage, several power plants were damaged.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] These include Sendai #4, New-Sendai #1 and #2, Haranomachi #1 and #2, Hirono #2 and #4 and Hitachinaka #1.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The Fukushima Daiichi, Fukushima Daini, Onagawa Nuclear Power Plant and Tōkai nuclear power stations, consisting of a total eleven reactors, were automatically shut down following the earthquake.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Higashidōri, also on the northeast coast, was already shut down for a periodic inspection.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Cooling is needed to remove decay heat after a Generation II reactor has been shut down, and to maintain spent fuel pools.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The backup cooling process is powered by emergency diesel generators at the plants and at Rokkasho nuclear reprocessing plant.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] At Fukushima Daiichi and Daini, tsunami waves overtopped seawalls and destroyed diesel backup power systems, leading to severe problems at Fukushima Daiichi, including three large explosions and radioactive leakage.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Subsequent analysis found that many Japanese nuclear plants, including Fukushima Daiichi, were not adequately protected against tsunamis.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The discharge of radioactive water in Fukushima was confirmed in later analysis at the three reactors at Fukushima I (Units 1, 2, and 3), which suffered meltdowns and continued to leak coolant water.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The aftershock on 7 April caused the loss of external power to Rokkasho Reprocessing Plant and Higashidori Nuclear Power Plant but backup generators were functional.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Onagawa Nuclear Power Plant lost three of its four external power lines and temporarily lost cooling function in its spent fuel pools for "20 to 80 minutes".
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A spill of "up to 3.8 litres [1.0 US gal]" of radioactive water also occurred at Onagawa following the aftershock.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A report by the IAEA in 2012 found that the Onagawa Nuclear Power Plant had remained largely undamaged.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In 2013, only two nuclear reactors in Japan had been restarted since the 2011 shutdowns.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In February 2019, there were 42 operable reactors in Japan.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Of these, only nine reactors in five power plants were operating after having been restarted post-2011.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Japan declared a state of emergency following the failure of the cooling system at the Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant, resulting in the evacuation of nearby residents.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Officials from the Japanese Nuclear and Industrial Safety Agency reported that radiation levels inside the plant were up to 1,000 times normal levels, and that radiation levels outside the plant were up to eight times normal levels.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Later, a state of emergency was also declared at the Fukushima Daini nuclear power plant about 11 km (6.8 mi) south.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Experts described the Fukushima disaster was not as bad as the Chernobyl disaster, but worse than the Three Mile Island accident.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The discharge of radioactive water of the Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant was later detected in tap water.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Radioactive iodine was detected in the tap water in Fukushima, Tochigi, Gunma, Tokyo, Chiba, Saitama, and Niigata, and radioactive caesium in the tap water in Fukushima, Tochigi and Gunma.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Radioactive caesium, iodine, and strontium were also detected in the soil in some places in Fukushima.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] There may be a need to replace the contaminated soil.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Many radioactive hotspots were found outside the evacuation zone, including Tokyo.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Radioactive contamination of food products were detected in several places in Japan.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In 2021, the Japanese cabinet finally approved the dumping of radioactive water in Fukushima into the Pacific Ocean over a course of 30 years, with full support of IAEA.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] To this day, the water is still actively being de-contaminated and is scheduled to be completed by the year 2051.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A fire occurred in the turbine section of the Onagawa Nuclear Power Plant following the earthquake.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The blaze was in a building housing the turbine, which is sited separately from the plant's reactor, and was soon extinguished.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The plant was shut down as a precaution.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] On 13 March the lowest-level state of emergency was declared regarding the Onagawa plant as radioactivity readings temporarily exceeded allowed levels in the area of the plant.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Tōhoku Electric Power Co. stated this may have been due to radiation from the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear accidents but was not from the Onagawa plant itself.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] As a result of the 7 April aftershock, Onagawa Nuclear Power Plant lost three of four external power lines and lost cooling function for as much as 80 minutes.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A spill of a couple of litres of radioactive water occurred at Onagawa.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The number 2 reactor at Tōkai Nuclear Power Plant was shut down automatically.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Japan's transport network suffered severe disruptions.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Many sections of Tōhoku Expressway serving northern Japan were damaged.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The expressway did not reopen to general public use until 24 March 2011.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] All railway services were suspended in Tokyo, with an estimated 20,000 people stranded at major stations across the city.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In the hours after the earthquake, some train services were resumed.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Most Tokyo area train lines resumed full service by the next day—12 March.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Twenty thousand stranded visitors spent the night of 11–12 March inside Tokyo Disneyland.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A tsunami flooded Sendai Airport at 15:55 JST, about one hour after the initial quake, causing severe damage.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Narita and Haneda Airport both briefly suspended operations after the quake, but suffered little damage and reopened within 24 hours.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Eleven airliners bound for Narita were diverted to nearby Yokota Air Base.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Various train services around Japan were also canceled, with JR East suspending all services for the rest of the day.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Four trains on coastal lines were reported as being out of contact with operators; one, a four-car train on the Senseki Line, was found to have derailed, and its occupants were rescued shortly after 8 am the next morning.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] There were no derailments of Shinkansen bullet train services in and out of Tokyo, but their services were also suspended.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The Tokaido Shinkansen resumed limited service late in the day and was back to its normal schedule by the next day, while the Jōetsu and Nagano Shinkansen resumed services late on 12 March.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Services on Yamagata Shinkansen resumed with limited numbers of trains on 31 March.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Derailments were minimized because of an early warning system that detected the earthquake before it struck.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The system automatically stopped all high-speed trains, which minimized the damage.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The Tōhoku Shinkansen line was worst hit, with JR East estimating that 1,100 sections of the line, varying from collapsed station roofs to bent power pylons, would need repairs.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Services on the Tōhoku Shinkansen partially resumed only in Kantō area on 15 March, with one round-trip service per hour between Tokyo and Nasu-Shiobara, and Tōhoku area service partially resumed on 22 March between Morioka and Shin-Aomori.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Services on Akita Shinkansen resumed with limited numbers of trains on 18 March.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Service between Tokyo and Shin-Aomori was restored by May, but at lower speeds due to ongoing restoration work; the pre-earthquake timetable was not reinstated until late September.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The rolling blackouts brought on by the crises at the nuclear power plants in Fukushima had a profound effect on the rail networks around Tokyo starting on 14 March.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Major railways began running trains at 10–20 minute intervals, rather than the usual 3–5 minute intervals, operating some lines only at rush hour and completely shutting down others; notably, the Tōkaidō Main Line, Yokosuka Line, Sōbu Main Line and Chūō-Sōbu Line were all stopped for the day.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] This led to near-paralysis within the capital, with long lines at train stations and many people unable to come to work or get home.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Railway operators gradually increased capacity over the next few days, until running at approximately 80% capacity by 17 March and relieving the worst of the passenger congestion.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] (left) and a damaged utility pole in Ishinomaki (right).
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Cellular and landline phone service suffered major disruptions in the affected area.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Immediately after the earthquake cellular communication was jammed across much of Japan due to a surge of network activity.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] On the day of the quake itself American broadcaster NPR was unable to reach anyone in Sendai with a working phone or access to the Internet.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Internet services were largely unaffected in areas where basic infrastructure remained, despite the earthquake having damaged portions of several undersea cable systems landing in the affected regions; these systems were able to reroute around affected segments onto redundant links.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Within Japan, only a few websites were initially unreachable.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] There was no loss of life, although the tsunami resulted in damage to all 18 Mitsubishi F-2 fighter jets of the 21st Fighter Training Squadron.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Twelve of the aircraft were scrapped, while the remaining six were slated for repair at a cost of 80 billion yen ($1 billion), exceeding the original cost of the aircraft.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] After the tsunami, elements of the Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force put to sea without orders and started rescuing those who had been washed out to sea.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Tsunami plans were for the Japan Self-Defense Forces assets to be led, directed, and coordinated by local civic governments.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] However, the earthquake destroyed town halls (the seat of local municipal government), police, and fire services in many places, so the military not only had to respond to but also command rescues.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Stone monuments at the UNESCO World Heritage Site: Shrines and Temples of Nikkō were toppled.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In Tokyo, there was damage to Koishikawa Kōrakuen, Rikugien, Hamarikyū Onshi Teien, and the walls of Edo Castle.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Information on the condition of collections held by museums, libraries and archives is still incomplete.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] There was no damage to the Historic Monuments and Sites of Hiraizumi in Iwate Prefecture, and the recommendation for their inscription on the UNESCO World Heritage List in June was seized upon as a symbol of international recognition and recovery.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The aftermath of the earthquake and tsunami included a humanitarian crisis and a major economic impact.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami resulted in over 340,000 displaced people in the Tōhoku region, and shortages of food, water, shelter, medicine, and fuel for survivors.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In response, the Japanese government mobilized the Self-Defense Forces (under Joint Task Force – Tōhoku, led by Lieutenant General Eiji Kimizuka), while many countries sent search and rescue teams to help search for survivors.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Aid organizations in Japan and worldwide responded, with the Japanese Red Cross reporting $1 billion in donations.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The economic impact included immediate problems, with industrial production suspended in many factories, and the longer term issue of the cost of rebuilding, which has been estimated at ¥10 trillion ($122 billion).
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In comparison to the 1995 Great Hanshin earthquake, the East Japan earthquake brought serious damage to an extremely wide range.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The aftermath of the twin disasters left Japan's coastal cities and towns with nearly 25 million tons of debris.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In Ishinomaki alone, there were 17 trash collection sites 180 meters (590 ft) long and at least 4.5 meters (15 ft) high.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] An official in the city's government trash disposal department estimated that it would take three years to empty these sites.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In April 2015, authorities off the coast of Oregon discovered debris that was thought to be from a boat destroyed during the tsunami.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The cargo contained yellowtail amberjack, a species of fish that lives off the coast of Japan, still alive.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] KGW estimates that more than 1 million tons of debris still remain in the Pacific Ocean.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In February 2016, a memorial was inaugurated by two architects for the victims of the disaster, consisting of a 6.5-square-metre (70 sq ft) structure on a hillside between a temple and a cherry tree in Ishinomaki.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The reconstruction of the Tohoku coast was funded and piloted by the Japanese government.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Structural adaptation to tsunamis was largely based on building higher seawalls, although seawalls proved largely ineffective in 2011, and the new seawalls would also not have been high enough.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Seismologists anticipated a very large quake would strike in the same place as the 1923 Great Kantō earthquake—in the Sagami Trough, southwest of Tokyo.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The Japanese government had tracked plate movements since 1976 in preparation for the so-called Tokai earthquake, predicted to take place in that region.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] However, occurring as it did 373 km (232 mi) north east of Tokyo, the Tōhoku earthquake came as a surprise to seismologists.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] While the Japan Trench was known for creating large quakes, it had not been expected to generate quakes above an 8.0 magnitude.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Also, a tsunami-earthquake with a tsunami magnitude scales (Mt) between 8.6 and 9.0 (Similar to the 1896 Sanriku earthquake, the Mt for the 2011 Tōhoku earthquake was 9.1–9.4) had a 30% chance to occur within 30 years.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The quake gave scientists the opportunity to collect a large amount of data to model the seismic events that took place in great detail.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] This data is expected to be used in a variety of ways, providing unprecedented information about how buildings respond to shaking, and other effects.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Gravimetric data from the quake have been used to create a model for increased warning time compared to seismic models, as gravity fields travel faster than seismic waves.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Researchers have also analysed the economic effects of this earthquake and have developed models of the nationwide propagation via interfirm supply networks of the shock that originated in the Tōhoku region.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] After the full extent of the disaster was known, researchers soon launched a project to gather all digital material relating to the disaster into an online searchable archive to form the basis of future research into the events during and after the disaster.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The Japan Disasters Digital Archive is presented in English and Japanese and is hosted at the Reischauer Institute of Japanese Studies at Harvard University in Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Some of the first research to come from the archive was a 2014 paper from the Digital Methods Initiative in Amsterdam about patterns of Twitter usage around the time of the disaster.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] At this time Japan's Disaster Management Office (Naikakufu Bosai Keikaku) published a bi-lingual guide in Japanese and English, *Disaster Management in Japan*, to outline the several varieties of natural disaster and the preparations being made for the eventuality of each.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The Japan Trench Fast Drilling Project, a scientific expedition conducted in 2012–2013, drilled ocean-floor boreholes through the fault zone of the earthquake and gathered important data about the rupture mechanism and physical properties of the fault that caused the 2011 earthquake and tsunami.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The 2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami had a great environmental impact on Japan's eastern coast.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The rarity and magnitude of the earthquake-tsunami prompted researchers Jotaro Urabe, Takao Suzuki, Tatsuki Nishita, and Wataru Makino to study their immediate ecological impacts on intertidal flat communities at Sendai Bay and the Sanriku Ria coast.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Pre- and post-event surveys show a reduction in animal taxon richness and change in taxon composition mainly attributed to the tsunami and its physical impacts.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] In particular, sessile epibenthic animals and endobenthic animals both decreased in taxon richness.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Mobile epibenthic animals, such as hermit crabs, were not as affected.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Post-surveys also recorded taxa that were not previously recorded before, suggesting that tsunamis have the potential to introduce species and change taxon composition and local community structure.
[src:honshu/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The long term ecological impacts at Sendai Bay and the greater east coast of Japan require further study.
[src:honshu/aichi-kōgen-quasi-national-park] Like all Quasi-National Parks in Japan, the park is managed by the local prefectural governments.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] Nagoya is the capital and largest city of Aichi Prefecture, and the fourth-largest city in Japan.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] Other major cities include Toyota, Okazaki, and Ichinomiya.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] Aichi Prefecture and Nagoya form the core of the Chūkyō metropolitan area, the third-largest metropolitan area in Japan and one of the largest metropolitan areas in the world.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] Aichi Prefecture is located on Japan's Pacific Ocean coast and forms part of the Tōkai region, a subregion of the Chūbu region and Kansai region.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] Aichi Prefecture is home to the Toyota Motor Corporation.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] Aichi Prefecture had many locations with the Higashiyama Zoo and Botanical Gardens, The Chubu Centrair International Airport, and the Legoland Japan Resort.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] Located near the centre of the Japanese main island of Honshu, Aichi Prefecture faces the Ise and Mikawa Bays to the south and borders Shizuoka Prefecture to the east, Nagano Prefecture to the northeast, Gifu Prefecture to the north, and Mie Prefecture to the west.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] It measures 106 km (66 mi) east to west and 94 km (58 mi) south to north and forms a major portion of the Nōbi Plain.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] With an area of 5,172.48 square kilometres (1,997.11 sq mi) it accounts for approximately 1.36% of the total surface area of Japan.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] The highest spot is Chausuyama at 1,415 m (4,642 ft) above sea level.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] The western part of the prefecture is dominated by Nagoya, Japan's third largest city, and its suburbs, while the eastern part is less densely populated but still contains several major industrial centres.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] Due to its robust economy, for the period from October 2005 to October 2006, Aichi was the fastest growing prefecture in terms of population, beating Tokyo, at 7.4% and around with after Saitama Prefecture.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] As of 1 April 2012, 23% of the total land area of the prefecture was designated as Natural Parks, namely the Aichi Kōgen, Hida-Kisogawa, Mikawa Wan, and Tenryū-Okumikawa Quasi-National Parks along with seven Prefectural Natural Parks.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] Thirty-eight cities are located in Aichi Prefecture.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] As of 2001, Aichi Prefecture's population was 50.03% male and 49.97% female.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] 139,540 residents (nearly 2% of the population) are of foreign nationality.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] Originally, the region was divided into two provinces of Owari and Mikawa.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] After the Meiji Restoration, Owari and Mikawa were united into a single entity.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] In 1871, after the abolition of the han system, Owari, with the exception of the Chita Peninsula, was established as Nagoya Prefecture, while Mikawa combined with the Chita Peninsula and formed Nukata Prefecture.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] Nagoya Prefecture was renamed to Aichi Prefecture in April 1872 and was united with Nukata Prefecture on 27 November of the same year.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] The government of Aichi Prefecture is located in the Aichi Prefectural Government Office in Nagoya, which is the old capital of Owari.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] The Aichi Prefectural Police and its predecessor organisations have been responsible for law enforcement in the prefecture since 1871.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] The Expo 2005 World Exposition was held in Seto and Nagakute.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] In the third volume of the *Man'yōshū* there is a poem by Takechi Kurohito that reads: "The cry of the crane, calling to Sakurada; it sounds like the tide, draining from Ayuchi flats, hearing the crane cry".
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] Ayuchi is the original form of the name *Aichi*, and the Fujimae tidal flat is all that remains of the earlier Ayuchi-gata.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] For a time, an Aichi Station existed on the Kansai Line (at the time the Kansai Railway) between Nagoya and Hatta stations, but its role was overtaken by Sasashima-raibu Station on the Aonami Line and Komeno Station on the Kintetsu Nagoya Line.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] Gross domestic product (2018) is the second largest in Japan, the shipment value of manufactured goods (2018) is the first in Japan, annual product sales (2019) is the third largest in Japan, and its agricultural output (2018) is eighth in Japan.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] Aichi's agriculture industry and commerce are all ranked high in Japan, and the industrial structure is well-balanced.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] Companies headquartered in Aichi include the following.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] Companies such as Fuji Heavy Industries, Mitsubishi Motors, Pfizer, Sony, Suzuki, Bodycote, and Volkswagen Group also operate plants or branch offices in Aichi.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] The sports teams listed below are based in Aichi.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] Notable sites in Aichi include the Meiji Mura open-air architectural museum in Inuyama, which preserves historic buildings from Japan's Meiji and Taishō periods, including the reconstructed lobby of Frank Lloyd Wright's old Imperial Hotel (which originally stood in Tokyo from 1923 to 1967).
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] Other popular sites in Aichi include the tour of Toyota car factory in the city by the same name, the monkey park in Inuyama, and the castles in Nagoya, Okazaki, Toyohashi, and Inuyama.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] Aichi Prefecture has many wonderful beaches.
[src:honshu/aichi-prefecture] For example, Himakajima Beach, Shinojima Beach, Akabane Beach and Utsumi Beach.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] The **Akashi Kaikyo Bridge** (Japanese: 明石海峡大橋, Hepburn: *Akashi Kaikyō Ōhashi*) is a suspension bridge that links the city of Kobe on the Japanese island of Honshu and Iwaya, Awaji on Awaji Island.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] It is part of the Kobe-Awaji-Naruto Expressway, and crosses the busy and turbulent Akashi Strait (*Akashi Kaikyō* in Japanese).
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] It was completed in 1998, and at the time, was the longest central span of any suspension bridge in the world, at 1,991 metres (6,532 ft).
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] Currently, it is the second-longest, behind the 1915 Çanakkale Bridge in Turkey that was opened in March 2022.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] The Akashi Kaikyo Bridge is one of the key links of the Honshū–Shikoku Bridge Project, which created three routes across the Seto Inland Sea.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] The Akashi Kaikyo Bridge forms part of the Kobe-Awaji-Naruto Expressway, the easternmost route of the bridge system linking the islands of Honshu and Shikoku.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] The bridge crosses the Akashi Strait (width 4 km) between Kobe on Honshu and Iwaya on Awaji Island; the other major part of the crossing is completed by the Ōnaruto Bridge, which links Awaji Island to Ōge Island across the Naruto Strait.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] Before the Akashi Kaikyo Bridge was built, ferries carried passengers across the Akashi Strait.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] A major passageway for shipping, it is also known for its gales, heavy rain, storms, and other natural disasters.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] The Sekirei Maru sinking in stormy weather in December 1945, while carrying more than three times its capacity of 100 passengers, killed 304 people, first stirring public discussion on the possibility of a bridge over the span.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] In 1955, two ferries sank in the Shiun Maru disaster during a storm, killing 168 people.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] The ensuing shock and public outrage convinced the Japanese government to develop plans for a bridge to cross the strait.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] Investigations for a bridge across the strait were first conducted by the Kobe municipal government in 1957, followed by an evaluation by the national Ministry of Construction in 1959.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] In 1961, the Ministry of Construction and Japan National Railways jointly commissioned the Japan Society of Civil Engineers (JSCE) to conduct a technical study, and the JSCE established a committee to investigate five potential routes between Honshu and Shikoku.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] In 1967, the committee compiled the results of the technical study, concluding that a bridge across the Akashi Strait would face "extremely severe design and construction conditions, which have no similar examples in the world's long-span bridges" and recommending an additional study.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] In response to the report, the Honshu–Shikoku Bridge Authority (now the Honshu-Shikoku Bridge Expressway Company) was established in 1970, which conducted extensive investigations, including sea trials to establish the construction method of a submarine foundation.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] In 1973, a bridge with a central span of 1,780 meters on the route was approved, but construction was halted due to poor economic conditions.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] The original plan called for a mixed railway-road bridge, but when construction on the bridge began in April 1988, it was restricted to road only, with six lanes.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] Actual construction did not begin until May 1988 and involved more than 100 contractors.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] The Great Hanshin Earthquake in January 1995 did not do substantial damage to the bridge due to anti-seismic building methods.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] Construction was finished on time in September 1996.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] The bridge was opened for traffic on April 5, 1998, in a ceremony officiated by the then-Crown Prince Naruhito and his spouse Crown Princess Masako of Japan along with Construction Minister Tsutomu Kawara.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] The bridge was the last Japanese megaproject of the 20th century.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] The bridge has four substructures: two main piers (located beneath the water) and two anchorages (on land).
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] These are denoted 1A, 2P, 3P, and 4A in sequence from the Kobe side.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] 1A consists of an underground circular retaining wall filled with roller-compacted concrete, 2P and 3P are circular underwater spread-foundation caisson structures, and 4A is a rectangular direct foundation.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] 2P is located at the edge of the sea plateau at a level depth of 40–50 m and a bearing depth of 60 m, and 3P is located at the symmetrical point to 2P with respect to the bridge's center, at a level depth of 36–39 m and a bearing depth of 57 m.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] The towers are located in an area of strong tidal currents where water velocity exceeds 7 knots (about 3.6 m/s).
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] The selected scour protection measure includes the installation of a filtering layer with a thickness of 2 m in a range of 10 m around the caisson, covered with riprap of 8 m thick.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] The central span is 1,991 m (6,532 ft), and the two other sections are each 960 m (3,150 ft).
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] The two towers were originally 1,990 m (6,530 ft) apart, but the Great Hanshin earthquake on January 17, 1995 (magnitude 7.3, with epicenter 20 km west of Kobe) moved the towers (the only structures that had been erected at the time) such that the central span had to be increased by 1 m (3.3 ft).
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] The central span was required to be greater than 1,500 m to accommodate maritime traffic; it was concluded before construction began that a larger span between 1950 and 2050 meters would minimize construction costs.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] The bridge was designed with a dual-hinged stiffening girder system, allowing the structure to withstand winds of 286 kilometres per hour (178 mph), earthquakes measuring up to magnitude 8.5, and harsh sea currents.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] The bridge also contains tuned mass dampers that are designed to operate at the resonance frequency of the bridge to damp forces.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] The two main supporting towers rise 282.8 m (928 ft) above sea level, and the bridge can expand because of heat by up to 2 m (6.6 ft) over the course of a day.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] Each anchorage required 350,000 tonnes (340,000 long tons; 390,000 short tons) of concrete.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] The steel cables have 300,000 kilometres (190,000 mi) of wire: each cable is 112 centimetres (44 in) in diameter and contains 36,830 strands of wire.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] The Akashi–Kaikyo bridge has a total of 1,737 illumination lights: 1,084 for the main cables, 116 for the main towers, 405 for the girders and 132 for the anchorages.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] Sets of three high-intensity discharge lamps in the colors red, green and blue are mounted on the main cables.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] The RGB color model and computer technology make for a variety of combinations.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] Twenty-eight patterns are used for occasions such as national or regional holidays, memorial days or festivities.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] The total cost is estimated at ¥500 billion or US$3.6 billion (per 1998 exchange rates).
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] It is expected to be repaid by charging drivers a toll to cross the bridge.
[src:honshu/akashi-kaikyo-bridge] The toll is 2,300 yen and the bridge is used by approximately 23,000 cars per day.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] The **Akita Inu** (秋田犬, *Akita Inu, Akita Ken*; Japanese pronunciation: [a.kʲi̥.ta(ꜜ) i.nɯ, -ta.keɴ]) is a Japanese dog breed of large size.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Originating from the mountains of northern Japan, the Akita has a short double coat similar to that of many other northern spitz breeds.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] However, it is subject to debate as to whether the Akita strains are distinct, or if they constitute one breed.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Outside of Japan, debate exists among fanciers whether these are two separate breeds of Akitas.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] As of 2020, the American Kennel Club now considers American and Japanese Akitas to be two separate breeds, no longer allowing free breeding between the two.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] The United Kennel Club, the Federation Cynologique Internationale (FCI), The Kennel Club, the Australian National Kennel Council, the New Zealand Kennel Club, and the Japan Kennel Club consider Japanese and American Akitas as separate breeds.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Some countries refer to the American Akita as simply the Akita and not the American Akita.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] The issue is especially controversial in Japan.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] For the FCI's 84 countries, the breed split formally occurred in June 1999, when the FCI decided that the American type would be called the Great Japanese Dog, later renamed the American Akita in January 2006.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] The direct ancestor of the Akita Inu was a dog kept as a guard dog and fighting dog by samurai and wealthy farmers in the Ōdate area, and was known as the Ōdate dog (大館犬) until 1931 when it was renamed the Akita Inu.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Since ancient times, hunting dogs called matagi dogs (マタギ犬) were kept in the Tōhoku region of northern Japan.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] The main targets of hunting were Asian black bears, Japanese serows, Japanese macaques, and rabbits.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] In Akita Prefecture, there was also a matagi dog called the Akita Matagi Inu (秋田マタギ犬), which is a medium-sized dog and is distinguished from the Akita Inu.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] During the Edo period (1603–1867), the Akita region was ruled by the Satake clan of the Kubota Domain.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] The Satake West Family (佐竹西家), the castle keeper of Ōdate Castle, is said to have nurtured the fighting spirit of its vassals through dogfighting.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] It is not known exactly how Akita Inu became larger, but according to a "discussion on dogs by old people" held in 1931 in the then Ōdate Town, a famous dog named "Moku" was kept at the Jō'ō-ji Temple (浄応寺) in Ōdate, commonly known as Naka no Tera Temple (中の寺), in the late Edo period (1603–1867).
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Moku was a dog born at the end of the Ansei era (1854–1860), lived through the fires of the Boshin War (1868–1869), and lived until 1871 or 1872.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Moku was about 85 cm tall at the shoulder and was large enough to carry an adult on its back.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Moku was a purely Japanese dog with erect ears and a curly tail, sesame (*goma*) in color, and long hair.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] If this theory is to be believed, Akita Inu had become larger by the end of the Edo period at the latest.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] In 1931, the Akita was officially declared a Japanese natural monument.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] The mayor of Odate City in Akita Prefecture organized the Akita Inu Hozonkai to preserve the original Akita as a Japanese natural treasure through careful breeding.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] In 1933, Heishiro Takaku (Takahisa), one of the early members of Nippo in Tokyo and later of the Nipponinu Kyokai (Nikkyo) in Osaka and Katsuichi (Shoichi) each published articles on a proposed Japanese dog standard, which Included the Akita dog.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Akita dogs revealed the most non-uniformity at that time, when compared to medium and small Japanese dogs, due to being outcrossed to the Tosa fighting dog, and other Imported foreign dogs.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] In 1934, the first Japanese breed standard for the Akita Inu was listed, following the breed's declaration as a natural monument of Japan.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] The Akita breed was used during the Russo-Japanese War to track prisoners of war and lost sailors.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] During World War II, the Akita was considered a non-military breed and was crossed with German Shepherds in an attempt to save them from the wartime government order for all non-military dogs to be culled.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Some were used as scouts and guards during the war.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] A native Japanese breed known as Matagi Inu (hunting dog) was used along with the Hokkaido Inu breed to mix back into the remaining Akita dogs to restore the breed.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] There were many lines of Akita, but the most influential were the Dewa and Ichinoseki.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Both lines contributed to the foundation stock for both Akita types, and many exported dogs were a combination of these lines.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] According to one Japanese judge, the greatest difference between Japanese- and American-bred Akitas is that the latter still show much evidence of the Dewa strain.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] In the early 1900s, Dewa-line Akitas were heavily favoured and did well in show.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Kongo-go (from the Heirakudo Kennel of Eikichi Hiraizumi) is considered to be the most influential dog of that line.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] However, the Dewa-line later went into a decline because Japanese breeders felt that the Akita did not give the impression of a Japanese dog, so began to breed towards an ideal type reminiscent of other Nihon-ken.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] The Dewa line was stereotyped as the “German Shepherd” type, while the Ichinoseki line was referred to as the “Mastiff” type.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Thus, the Ichinoseki-line rose in popularity.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Goromaru-Go was regarded as the most influential Akita of that line who, although did not perform well in show, produced outstanding Akita dogs when bred to Taihei and Nikkei lines from Southern Akita.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] During the occupation years following the war, the breed began to thrive again through the efforts of Sawataishi and others.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Morie Sawataishi and his efforts to breed the Akita is a major reason this breed exists today.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] For the first time, Akitas were bred for a standardized appearance.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Akita fanciers in Japan began gathering and exhibiting the remaining Akitas and producing litters to restore the breed to sustainable numbers and to accentuate the ideal characteristics of the breed muddied by crosses to other breeds.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] It was not until the 1960–1970s where the foxier Japanese type started to diverge from the typical American type.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] The story of Hachikō helped push the Akita into the international dog world.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Hachikō was born in 1923 and owned by Professor Hidesaburō Ueno of Tokyo.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Professor Ueno lived near the Shibuya Train Station in a suburb of the city, and commuted to work every day on the train.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Hachikō accompanied his master to and from the station each day.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] On May 25, 1925, when the dog was 18 months old, he waited for his master's arrival on the four o'clock train, but Professor Ueno had suffered a fatal brain haemorrhage at work.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Hachikō continued to wait for his master's return.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] He travelled to and from the station each day for the next nine years.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] He allowed the professor's relatives to care for him, but he never gave up the vigil at the station for his master.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] His vigil became world-renowned when, in 1934, shortly before his death, a bronze statue was erected at the Shibuya train station in his honor.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] This statue was melted down for munitions during the war, but a new one was commissioned after the war.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Each year on March 8 since 1936, Hachikō's devotion has been honoured with a solemn ceremony of remembrance at Tokyo's Shibuya railroad station.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Eventually, Hachikō's legendary faithfulness became a national symbol of loyalty, particularly to the person and institution of the Emperor.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] In 1967, commemorating the 50th anniversary of the founding of Akita Inu Hozonkai (AKIHO, Akita Dog Preservation Society), the Akita Dog Museum was built to house information, documents and photos.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] In 1937, Helen Keller travelled to Japan.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] She expressed a keen interest in the breed and was presented with the first two Akitas to enter the US.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Ogasawara and named Kamikaze-go, died at 7+1⁄2 months of age from distemper, one month after her return to the States.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] A second Akita was arranged to be sent to Keller: Kamikaze's litter brother, Kenzan-go.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Keller nicknamed the dog Go-Go and they were great companions from day one.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Go-Go even spent his first night at Keller's home sleeping at the foot of her bed.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] By 1939, a breed standard had been established and dog shows had been held, but such activities stopped after World War II began.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] The Japanese Akita and American Akita began to diverge in type post-World War II due to America and Europe preserving the Akitas that fell out of favour in Japan, particularly the Dewa-types and dogs with the signature black mask or pinto marking.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] American Akitas are typically considered mixed by Japanese breeders (and not true Akitas by the Japanese standard).
[src:honshu/akita-dog] However, their phenotype predates the Japanese Akita by a few decades, and they are closer to pre-war Akitas like Hachiko.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Helen Keller is credited with bringing the Akita to America after being given two Akitas by the Japanese government in 1938.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] By 1939, a breed standard was established, and dog shows began to be held, but this development was interrupted by World War II.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] During this time, US servicemen serving as part of the occupation force in Japan first came into contact with the Akita.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] The breed so impressed them that many service members chose to bring an Akita back home with them upon completion of their tour.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Although both types derive from common ancestry, marked differences are seen between the two.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] American Akitas generally are heavier boned and larger, with a more bear-like head, whereas Japanese Akitas tend to be lighter and more finely featured with a fox-like head.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Additionally, while American Akitas are acceptable in all colors, Japanese Akitas are only permitted to be red, white, or brindle.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Additionally, American Akitas may be pinto and/or have black masks, unlike Japanese Akitas, where these are considered disqualifications and are not permitted in the breed standards.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Recognized by the American Kennel Club in 1955, the Akita was placed in the Miscellaneous class.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] The AKC did not approve the Akita standard until 1972, and it was moved to the Working Dog class.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] As such, the Akita is a rather new breed in the United States.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Foundation stock in America continued to be imported from Japan until 1974, when the AKC cut off registration to any further Japanese imports until 1992, when it recognized the Japan Kennel Club standards.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] This decision set the stage for the divergence in type between the American Akita and Japanese Akita Inu that is present today.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Elsewhere in the world, one American Akita was first introduced to the UK in 1937.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] He was a Canadian import, owned by a Mrs.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Jenson live on today breeding American Akitas.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] The most widely known of these is Joseph Felton, an award-winning Akita breeder, but the breed was not itself widely known until the early 1980s.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] The breed was introduced in Australia in 1982 with an American import and to New Zealand in 1986 with an import from the UK.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] As a spitz breed, the appearance of the Akita reflects cold-weather adaptations essential to their original function.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] The Akita is a substantial breed for its height with heavy bones.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Characteristic physical traits of the breed include a large, bear-like head with erect, triangular ears set at a slight angle following the arch of the neck.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Additionally, the eyes of the Akita are small, dark, deeply set, and triangular in shape.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Akitas have thick double coats, and tight, well-knuckled, cat-like feet.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Their tails are carried over the tops of their backs in a gentle or double curl down the loin.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Mature American-type males measure typically 26-28 in (66–71 cm) at the withers and weigh between 100 and 130 lb (45–59 kg).
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Mature females typically measure 24-26 in (61–66 cm) and weigh between 70 and 100 lb (32–45 kg).
[src:honshu/akita-dog] The Japanese type, as stated in the breed standards, is a little smaller and lighter.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Breed standards state that all dog breed coat colors and patterns are allowable in the American Akita.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] This includes the common Shiba Inu coloring pattern known as *urajiro*.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] The Japanese Akitas, as per the breed standards, are restricted to red, fawn, sesame, brindle, and pure white, all with *urajiro* markings - whitish coat on the sides of the muzzle, on the cheeks, on the underside of jaw, neck, chest, body, and tail, and on the inside of the legs.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] The two coat types in the Akita are the standard coat length and the long coat.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] The long coat is considered a fault in the show ring, however.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] The long coat, also known as *moku*, is the result of an autosomal recessive gene and may occur phenotypically only if both sire and dam are carriers.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] They have longer (about 3-4 in long) and softer coats and are known to have sweeter temperaments.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] This gene is thought to come from the Karafuto Ken dog.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] The Akita is generally seen as territorial about its property, and can be reserved with strangers.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] The breed has been defined in some countries' breed-specific legislation as a dangerous dog.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] The Akita is a large, strong, independent, and dominant dog.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] A well-trained Akita should be accepting of nonthreatening strangers, otherwise they treat all strangers in an aggressive manner.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] A survey on canine behaviour in five 'ancient' breeds in Poland found the Akita to be the most aggressive towards other dogs with 59% of Akitas being reported to display aggression towards other dogs and animals.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] They were the second most likely to be aggressive towards humans with 13% of Akitas being reported to display aggression towards humans.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Stereotypic behaviour was reported in 27% of Akitas, ranking it second out of the five breeds surveyed.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Excessive vocalisation was only reported at 17% for the Akita, lower than the other breeds.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Less than 10% of Akitas were reported to have separation anxiety, the lowest amount.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] 70% of all human directed aggression involved a visitor on the Akita's territory, highlighting the defensive nature of the breed.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] A Japanese study found that the CAG repeat polymorphism in the AR gene in the Akita Inu was correlated with increased reports of aggression in male Akita dogs, but not females.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] A UK study found a life expectancy of 11.4 years for the breed compared to an average of 12.7 for purebreeds and 12 for crossbreeds.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Predecessors of the modern Akita were used for hunting bear, wild boar, and deer in Japan as late as 1957.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] They would be used to flush out the boar and keep it at bay until the hunter could come and kill it.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] The Akita Inu Hozonkai (AKIHO; Akita Inu Preservation Society) is a public interest incorporated association whose purpose is to protect and breed the Akita Inu.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] In the late Meiji period, the dog-fighting craze grew, and the trend to breed stronger dogs became stronger.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] In this time, pure Akita Inu were on the verge of extinction due to crossbreeding with other dog breeds such as the Tosa.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] **Akita Inu Hozonkai** was founded in 1927, and in 1954 it was merged with the **Akita Dog Preservation Association** to form the current organization.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] The Akita Inu Hozonkai was established in May 1927 by Izumi Shigeie, who was the mayor of Odate Town in Kitaakita District, Akita Prefecture at the time.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] In 1931, the Akita Inu became the first domestic dog breed to be designated as a natural monument, and around 1934, dog registration began.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] In 1938, the Akita Inu standard was established.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] In 1936, the Akita Inu Preservation Association was established as a prefecture-wide organization, with Akita Prefecture Governor Masasuke Kodama as its chairman.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] During the Pacific War, the bloodline was continued by crossbreeding with shepherds, the only dogs approved for military use in Japan, but the breed regressed significantly from the Akita lineage that had been preserved.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] After the war, efforts to restore the lineage were resumed using the few remaining Akitas.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] The Akita Inu Preservation Society resumed exhibitions in 1947, and began publishing its newsletter, the "Akita Inu," in 1949.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Akita Inu Hozonkai transitioned to an incorporated association in May 1953.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] In 1954, the Akita Inu Preservation Society and the Akita Inu Preservation Association were merged to form the current organization.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] Since then, the organization has expanded its branches nationwide and even established branches overseas.
[src:honshu/akita-dog] In May 2015, it transitioned to a public interest incorporated association.
[src:honshu/honshu] Honshu had a population of 100.7 million as of 2025, constituting 81.9% of the entire population of Japan, and mostly concentrated in the coastal areas and plains.
[src:honshu/honshu] Approximately 30% of the total population resides in the Greater Tokyo Area on the Kantō Plain.
[src:honshu/honshu] As the historical center of Japanese cultural and political power, the island includes several past Japanese capitals, including Kyoto, Nara, and Kamakura.
[src:honshu/honshu] Much of the island's southern shore forms part of the Taiheiyō Belt, a megalopolis that spans several of the Japanese islands.
[src:honshu/honshu] Honshu also contains Japan's highest mountain, Mount Fuji, and its largest lake, Lake Biwa.
[src:honshu/honshu] Most of Japan's industry is located in a belt running along Honshu's southern coast, from Tokyo to Nagoya, Kyoto, Osaka, Kobe, and Hiroshima.
[src:honshu/honshu] The island is linked to the other three major Japanese islands by a number of bridges and tunnels.
[src:honshu/honshu] The island primarily shares two climates, with Northern Honshu having four seasons with largely varying temperatures while the south experiences long, hot summers and cool to mild winters.
[src:honshu/honshu] The name of the island, Honshū (本州), stems from Middle Chinese.
[src:honshu/honshu] It directly translates to "main province" or "home land" in English.
[src:honshu/honshu] Humans first arrived in Honshu at least approximately 37,000 years ago.
[src:honshu/honshu] The first humans to arrive in Honshu were Stone Age hunter-gatherers from Northeast Asia, likely following the migration of ice age megafauna.
[src:honshu/honshu] Surviving artifacts from this period include finely crafted stone blades, similar to those found in Siberia.
[src:honshu/honshu] After the initial arrival of hunter-gatherers, the island saw the emergence of the Jōmon period (c.
[src:honshu/honshu] 14,000–300 BCE), one of the earliest known eras of prehistoric Japanese culture.
[src:honshu/honshu] The Jōmon people were known for their distinctive cord-marked pottery and dogū clay figurines, many of which have been excavated at archaeological sites across Honshu.
[src:honshu/honshu] These artifacts reflect a complex spiritual life and early forms of sedentary communities, particularly along the coasts and river valleys.
[src:honshu/honshu] The Meiji Restoration, in Japanese history, is the political revolution in 1868 that brought the final demise of the Tokugawa shogunate (which was a military government).
[src:honshu/honshu] It ended the Edo (Tokugawa) Period (1603–1867) and at least nominally returned control of the country to direct imperial rule under Mutsuhito (the Emperor Meiji).
[src:honshu/honshu] One of the main leaders of the restoration (who were mostly young samurai) was Chōshū in far western Honshu, which was one of the feudal areas, hostile to Tokugawa authority domains.
[src:honshu/honshu] The island is roughly 1,300 km (810 mi) long and ranges from 50 to 230 km (31 to 143 mi) wide, and its total area is 227,960 km2 (88,020 sq mi).
[src:honshu/honshu] Its land area has been increasing with land reclamation and coastal uplift in the north due to plate tectonics with a convergent boundary.
[src:honshu/honshu] Honshu has 10,084 kilometres (6,266 mi) of coastline.
[src:honshu/honshu] The highest peak is the active volcano Mount Fuji at 3,776 m (12,388 ft), which makes Honshu the world's 7th highest island.
[src:honshu/honshu] There are many rivers, including the Shinano River, Japan's longest.
[src:honshu/honshu] The Japanese Alps span the width of Honshu, from the 'Sea of Japan' coast to the Pacific shore.
[src:honshu/honshu] Western Japan experiences a temperate climate with hot summers and cool to mild winters.
[src:honshu/honshu] In addition to the general climate patterns, central Honshu, particularly the regions surrounding the Japanese Alps, experiences heavy snowfall in winter.
[src:honshu/honshu] Areas such as Niigata, Toyama, and Nagano prefectures are renowned for their snow accumulation, making them popular destinations for skiing and winter sports.
[src:honshu/honshu] These regions are among the snowiest inhabited places in the world, due to the humid air masses from the Sea of Japan colliding with the mountainous terrain.
[src:honshu/honshu] Honshu has a total population of 100.7 million people, according to the 2025 Census, 81.9% of the entire population of Japan.
[src:honshu/honshu] The largest city is Tokyo (population 14,246,219), the capital of Japan and part of the Greater Tokyo Area, one of the most populous metropolitan areas in the world.
[src:honshu/honshu] Honshu is connected to the islands of Hokkaido, Kyushu and Shikoku by tunnels and bridges.
[src:honshu/honshu] These are notable flora and fauna of Honshu.
[src:honshu/honshu] Being on the Ring of Fire, the island of Honshu is seismically active, and is home to 40 active volcanoes.
[src:honshu/honshu] In 2011, an earthquake of magnitude 9.0–9.1 occurred off the east coast of Honshu, generating tsunami waves up to 40.5 meters (133 ft) high that were observed all across the Pacific, and killing 19,759.
[src:honshu/honshu] It was the most powerful earthquake ever recorded in Japan, and the fourth most powerful earthquake in the world since modern record-keeping began in 1900.
[src:honshu/honshu] The tsunami subsequently led to the meltdown of 3 nuclear reactors at the Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant, leading to the Fukushima nuclear disaster.
[src:honshu/honshu] Honshu island generates around US$3.5 trillion or more than 80% of Japan's GDP.
[src:honshu/honshu] Fruit, vegetables, grains, rice and cotton make up the main produce grown in Honshu.
[src:honshu/honshu] The Tōhoku region, spanning the north-eastern part of the island, is notable for its rice production, with 65% of cultivated land being rice paddy fields – almost a quarter of all paddy fields in Japan.
[src:honshu/honshu] Chiba Prefecture is famous for its peanuts, also being the largest producer in Japan.
[src:honshu/honshu] Rare species of the lichen genus Menegazzia are found only in Honshu.
[src:honshu/honshu] Most of Japan's tea and silk is from Honshu.
[src:honshu/honshu] Japan's three largest industrial regions are all located on Honshu: the Keihin region, the Hanshin Industrial Region, and the Chūkyō Industrial Area.
[src:honshu/honshu] Honshu is home to a large portion of Japan's minimal mineral reserves, including small oil and coal deposits.
[src:honshu/honshu] Several coal deposits are located in the northern part of the island, concentrated in Fukushima Prefecture and Niigata Prefecture, though Honshu's coal production is negligible in comparison to Hokkaido and Kyushu.
[src:honshu/honshu] Most of Japan's oil reserves are also located in northern Honshu, along the west coast, spanning Niigata, Yamagata, and Akita Prefectures.
[src:honshu/honshu] Most of Japan's copper, lead, zinc and chromite is located on Honshu, along with smaller, scattered deposits of gold, silver, arsenic, sulfur and pyrite.
[src:honshu/honshu] The Tokaido Shinkansen, opened in 1964 between Tokyo and Shin-Ōsaka, is Japan's first high-speed rail line.
[src:honshu/honshu] It is the world's oldest high-speed rail line and one of the most heavily used.
[src:honshu/honshu] The San'yō Shinkansen connects stations in the two largest cities in western Japan, Shin-Osaka in Osaka with Hakata Station in Fukuoka.
[src:honshu/honshu] Both the Tokaido Shinkansen and the Sanyo Shinkansen help form a continuous high-speed railway through the Taiheiyō Belt megalopolis.
[src:honshu/honshu] The island is divided into five nominal regions and contains 34 prefectures, including metropolitan Tokyo.
[src:honshu/honshu] Administratively, some smaller islands are included within these prefectures, notably including the Ogasawara Islands, Sado Island, Izu Ōshima, and Awaji Island.
